<HEADLINE> TB Resurrects Because Of AIDS, Says WHO Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- About 300 million people will
be infected with tuberculosis (TB) in the next decade, the latest
World Health Organisation (WHO) report says.
</P>
<P>
Of them, 90 million will have developed full-blown disease and
30 million will have died of it, the report says.
</P>
<P>
The report says about three million people will die of the
disease annually, accounting for seven percent of all the deaths
in the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
It says one person is infected with TB virus per second in the
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The report says the resurgence of TB, which has almost been
wiped out with the discovery of anti-biotics, is a result of the
Aids epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The air-transmitted disease accounts for more than 25 percent
of all the adults deaths that could have been prevented,
according to the report. enditem

