<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Policemen Begin Deploying For Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Palestinian
policemen began deploying this afternoon around almost 1,700
polling stations throughout the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The policemen will police the Palestinian elections on
Saturday. Three uniformed policemen will be stationed at each
polling booth and one of them is armed with a pistol.
</P>
<P>
The deployment has been in coordination with the Israeli
military authorities and will continue through Friday.
</P>
<P>
Most outstanding issues between Israel and the Palestinian
Authority over the elections have been reportedly resolved. It
was agreed at a meeting between Maj.-Gen. Oren Shahor,
Coordinator of Government activities in the Territories, and Abu
Mazen, Head of the Palestinian Central Election Commission, that
local municipal inspectors in Hebron will oversee the voting.
</P>
<P>
The inspectors will not be in uniform, nor will they carry
weapons. They will also be deployed at polling stations in areas
still under Israel's control in the West Bank, as well as in post
offices in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In east Jerusalem, some 4,500 Palestinian voters will cast
their votes in five Israeli-run post offices. The rest will go
voting outside the Jerusalem municipality boundary. The Jerusalem
police will be responsible for security of the elections in east
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, leaders of right-wing groups, who are planning to
protest the elections in east Jerusalem, announced today they
will not disrupt the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
