<HEADLINE> World Food Situation Deteriorating: Fao Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Director-General of
the Food and Agriculture Organization (Fao) Jacques Diouf today
said the world food situation has been deteriorating as 800
million people are experiencing food shortage.
</P>
<P>
While paying a courtesy call on Zambian deputy Foreign
Minister Peter Machungwa in Lusaka, Diouf said his organization
plans to host a world food summit from November 13 to 17, at
which the heads of state can discuss the world food situation.
</P>
<P>
Another meeting will be held in April at ministerial level in
Burkina Faso to devise an African way of solving the food problem
in the continent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the world's population is growing everyday, there is
need to find a permanent solution to the food problem, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Fao chief, who arrived here today for a
three-day visit, said his tour of Zambia will afford him an
opportunity to analyse the food situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped to hold fruitful consultative meetings with
Zambian officials on how to find solutions to the deteriorating
food situation in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
It is Diouf's first visit to the southern African country
since he took the post in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
