<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile of New Greek Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Costas Simitis was elected new
Greek prime minister today in the ruling Panhellenic Socialist
Movement (PASOK) parliamentary group to replace PASOK leader
Andreas Papandreou who resigned as prime minister on Monday for
health reason.
</P>
<P>
Born in Piraeus in 1936, Simitis followed the family law
tradition by studying law in germany. He went on to study economics
at the london school of economics before returning to Greece in 1965.
</P>
<P>
Following the military take-over in 1967, Simitis and others
jointly founded the the "democratic defense" organization to fight
the military junta.
</P>
<P>
He was persecuted by the junta for, among other things, planting
bombs, and escaped abroad where he joined Panhellenic Liberation
Movement (PAK), the precursor to today's PASOK.
</P>
<P>
He subsequently became a university lecturer in germany. He
returned to Athens in 1974 and was a co-founder of PASOK.
</P>
<P>
In 1981, in the first PASOK government, he was appointed
agriculture minister, a post which he retained until 1985.
Immediately afterwards, he became national economy minister.
In 1993 he took over the commerce and industry portfolio, only
to resign from the ministry and from PASOK's executive bureau
following a clash with Andreas Papandreou.
</P>
<P>
Simitis is renowned for his cool-headedness. He is married to
Daphne Arcadiou and has two daughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
