<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Refugees Flee Fighting in Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Rwandan refugees
are fleeing toward Burundi's border with Tanzania today after the
outbreak of fierce fighting in northeast Burundi forced the
closure of their camp, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
"As of last night Mugano camp has been closed and doesn't
exist any more because of very heavy fighting in the area," said
Mise Hitoshi, UN High Commissioner for Refugees (Unhcr) head in
the Burundi capital of Bujumbura.
</P>
<P>
"Only a few hundred refugees remain in the camp and 15,000
refugees are moving toward the Tanzanian border through fear of
fighting," Hitoshi said. The border is six kilometers east of
Mugano.
</P>
<P>
"There are no reports of humanitarian or civilian casualties
so far but we don't know who the fighting is between. Civilians
and refugees are not believed to have been implicated," Hitoshi
said.
</P>
<P>
Hutu rebels and the Tutsi-dominated army are fighting a civil
war centred in northern Burundi, which is also the site of most
refugee camps for some 152,000 Rwandan Hutu refugees.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000 Rwandan refugees tried to flee insecurity in
northeastern Burundi last April, and their exodus was stopped by
Tanzanian troops deployed on the border to block them.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,500 refugees however managed to cross into Tanzania,
which argues it is already overwhelmed by 750,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan Hutus fled to troubled Burundi in 1994 during the
genocide of about half a million Tutsis and Hutu moderates by
Hutu troops, militiamen and mobs. Most say they fear being killed
in reprisal for the mass slaughter if they return home.
</P>
<P>
The camp was closed after Unhcr leader Sadako Ogata said she
wanted an urgent mission sent to Burundi to investigate security
measures including deployment of guards to protect UN staff.
</P>
<P>
While reporting to UN secretary-general Boutros Boutros-Ghali
on her visit to Burundi this month, Ogata also suggested that
military observers from the Organization of African Unity might
serve as liasion between aid groups and the Burundi military.
</P>
<P>
Boutros-Ghali, presenting his report based on Ogata's visit,
warned the security council yesterday that there is a real danger
Burundi might again explode into ethnic violence on a massive
scale.
</P>
<P>
"I continue to believe that it is imperative for the
international community to launch a major initiative to prevent
another tragedy in the subregion as well as to promote a dialogue
embracing all elements of the Burundi politicalion spectrum," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief has suggested guards for aid workers as well as a
rapid-reaction military force of 4,000 peacekeepers stationed in
neighboring Zaire. Key security council members such as the US
and Britain have rejected any peacekeeping force at this time but
said they would accept guards.
</P>
<P>
Over 100,000 people of a population of about 6 million have
been killed in the last two years since the killing of Burundi's
first freely-elected Hutu president by Tutsi troops.
</P>
<P>
Most agencies pulled out of north Burundi last month after a
wave of attacks but some including the Unhcr and the
International Red Cross resumed work in the last two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
