<HEADLINE> (Updated)Costas Simitis Elected New Greek PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Costas Simitis, former minister
of commerce and industry, was today elected Greece's new prime
minister to replace ailing Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK)
Party leader Andreas Papandreou who resigned as prime minister
earlier this week for health reason.
</P>
<P>
Simitis was elected by the ruling Socialist Party's
parliamentary group after receiving 86 votes against 75 votes of
his main rival Akis Tsochatzopoulos in the crucial second round of
voting. Six were blank votes.
</P>
<P>
National Defense Minister Gerassimos Arsenis and former
national defense minister Yiannis Charalambopoulos were eliminated
in the first round of voting.
</P>
<P>
The new premier designate is expected to be given a mandate to
form a government by President Kostis Stephanopoulos by tomorrow
morning.
</P>
<P>
Simitis has three days to put together a new cabinet, after
which he will have two weeks to prepare and present his
government's policy statements and seek a vote of confidence from
the 350-seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
PASOK has 169 seats in the house, but in today's ballot behind
closed doors only 167 deputies cast their vote, as Papandreou
remains hospitalized and another deputy died yesterday and was not
replaced in time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
