<HEADLINE> EC to Set Up Representative Office in Sarajevo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC)
is going to set up a representative office in Sarajevo to
administer the "Essential Aid Programme" for Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference this afternoon, Van den Broek, the EC
Commissioner responsible for foreign affairs in Europe, told
reporters that a EC convoy of vehicles will leave for Sarajevo
tomorrow, carring equipment and personnel to set up the EC's
representative office in the city.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Office will administer the "Essential Aid
Programme" outlined by the First Donor's Meeting on the
Reconstruction of Bosnia-Herzegovina held in Brussels on December
20-21, 1995.
</P>
<P>
At this first donor's meeting, 50 countries and 27
organizations pledged between them some 500 million U.S. dollars
earmarked for use in the first quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the Commissioner, the Office, which will be headed
by Joannes ter Haar, the EC's Special Envoy to Bosnia-Herzegovina,
will help set up a framework of donor coordination, in conjunction
with the World Bank, and will liaise with central and local
authorities to establish medium and long term reconstruction
strategy.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Van den Broek said, the office will set up close
coordination with the various agencies involved in the
reconstruction process, and "especially with the International
Management Group and the office of the High Representative, Mr.
Carl Bildt".
</P>
<P>
He said that out of European Union funds up to one billion
ECU(about 1.3 billion U.S. dollars) could be earmarked for
reconstruction purposes in the war-thorn areas of former
Yugoslavia for the four years 1996 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
"This is entirely separate from the humanitarian aid given to
ex-Yugoslavia by ECHO(European Community Humanitarian Office)," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
