<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gaddafi: It Is Hard to Clear Arab Atmosphere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi
said today at Sidi Barrani near the Egyptian-Libyan border that it
is hard to clear the Arab atmosphere and achieve inter-Arab
reconciliation at present.
</P>
<P>
At a brief joint press conference held with Mubarak following
their three-hour meeting at the Sidi Barrani military base, some
80 kilometers east of the border, Gaddafi accused some Arab
countries of calling for division of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He warned the Arab countries of challenges facing the Arab
world.
</P>
<P>
Because of the air ban, Gaddafi traveled by land to Egypt
earlier today on his first visit to the neighboring country since
January 1995.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak told reporters that he discussed with the Libyan head
of state the current situation in the Arab world, inter-Arab
cooperation and other Arab issues.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said he never stopped consultations with Gaddafi.
</P>
<P>
"Perhaps it has been a long time since we last met ... but our
talks were maintained either through the phone or via messages
dispatched by delegates," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president said that they could not get into
details during their talks because the time was too limited.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi accused Sudan of sponsoring terrorism though he said
that his country enjoys a normal relationship with Sudan.
</P>
<P>
He added that Libya is trying to use the normal relationship to
heal the rift between Sudan and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders had been expected to discuss the Libya-West
crisis, but neither of them commented on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed air, arms and diplomatic embargo on
Libya in April 1992 after Libya refused to comply with a Western
demand for extraditing two Libyan nationals, who were suspected of
bombing a Pan Am passenger plane over Lockerbie, Scotland, in
1988. A total of 270 people were killed in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain insist that the suspects be tried
in the U.S. or Britain while Libya insists that they be tried in a
neutral country or in the International Court of Justice in the
Hague.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Gaddafi denied there is any problem
related to the Egyptian workforce in Libya.
</P>
<P>
"All Arabs and Libyans in the country live and work together
without any problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian press have accused the Libyan authorities of their
ill treatment to the Egyptians working in Libya.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan leader told the news conference that Libya has great
potentials in its investments in Egypt, which he said has created
a very appropriate atmosphere for investments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Egyptian Information Minister Safwat el-Sherif, who
accompanied Gaddafi from the border to the military base before
the talks, said that the visit by Gaddafi came within the context
of the "strong and close" relations between Egypt and Libya.
</P>
<P>
After the press conference, Gaddafi left for home in his
car, which drove away to el-Saloum border checkpoint on the way to
Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
