<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls For Budget Talks Resumption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Thursday urged Republican congressional leaders to resume
high-level talks, saying a balanced budget "is clearly within our
grasp".
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Clinton said, "My door is open. It is
open. It will stay open. I am committed to continue working with
them until we get the job done."
</P>
<P>
Republican leaders canceled a scheduled White House meeting on
Wednesday, asking for a firm budget offer from Clinton that can
get bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
White House aides said Clinton was considering unveiling a new
budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said a budget deal is still possible because both sides
already have agreed to enough budget cuts. Policy differences,
such as how Medicare is funded, can wait until the election, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We already have agreement on way more than enough budget
savings to balance this budget," Clinton said. "It is wrong for us
to defer this."
</P>
<P>
Both sides said that they were prepared to go back to the
negotiating table when the circumstances were right.
</P>
<P>
Clinton on Wednesday talked on the phone for 40 minutes to
Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole, Gingrich and House Majority
Leader Dick Armey.
</P>
<P>
Dole said the president was "forthcoming" and "did indicate
some flexibility," but adding, "We indicated to the president that
we didn't see any real purpose in going to the White House unless
he had some new proposal to give us."
</P>
<P>
The two sides remain divided over the level of Medicare and
Medicaid savings, the extent of a tax cut and Republican plans to
enact fundamental changes to federal health and welfare systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
