<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, Israel Sign Cooperation Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and Israel signed four
agreements on cooperation between them in Aqaba today, completing
the signing of all agreements in accordance with their peace
treaty.
</P>
<P>
The agreements, which are the last batch of a total of 13
agreements required to be signed under the 1994 Jordanian-Israeli
historic peace treaty, cover the areas of science and culture,
telecommunications and maritime boundary as well as the
Aqaba-Eilat development program.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan and Israeli Prime Minister Shimon
Peres, who arrived in Aqaba earlier today, attended the signing
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdul Karim Kabariti and his Israeli
counterpart Ehud Barak signed the science and culture accord,
while communications ministers of both countries put their
signatures on the telecommunications agreement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two other accords, on maritime boundary and the
Aqaba-Eilat development program respectively, were also signed by
officials from the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The four agreements will pave the way for further cooperation
between the two countries, said Radio Jordan.
</P>
<P>
After the ceremony, the Crown Prince and the Israeli prime
minister delivered speeches assessing the Middle East peace
process and bilateral relations under the peace treaty. They also
evaluated the importance of the coming phases in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Following their speeches, all the participants in the ceremony
went to the neighboring Israeli port city of Eilat for a dinner
hosted by Peres in honor of the Crown Prince and his 250-member
delegation of officials, diplomats and journalists.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on transportation signed Tuesday was widely
acclaimed here as the "linchpin" of all the agreements signed
between the two countries, because it consolidates the eight other
cooperation agreements signed before, including a trade agreement
and an agreement on tourism.
</P>
<P>
The transport agreement permits the flow of goods to the
Palestinian self-rule areas and facilitates the exchange of goods
and tourists between Jordan and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The other bilateral accords signed last year include those on
health and medicine, energy, environment protection, agriculture,
border crossing points and combating crime and drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
