<HEADLINE> Peres Arrives in Aqaba to Attend Signing Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Shimon
Peres arrived in Jordan's Red Sea port city of Aqaba today to
attend the signing ceremony of the last batch of bilateral
agreements under the Jordanian-Israeli peace treaty signed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Peres was greeted at Aqaba airport by Crown Prince Hassan and
Jordanian Prime Minister Sharif Zeid Ben Shaker.
</P>
<P>
Prince Hassan and Peres will patronize the signing of the
agreements on science and culture, telecommunications and Maritime
Boundary as well as the accord on Aqaba-Eilat Development, the
last batch of the 13 agreements supposed to be concluded under the
peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Abdul Karim Kabariti and his Israeli
counterpart Ehud Barak will sign the science and culture accord,
while communications ministers of both countries will sign the
telecommunications agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Maritime Boundary and Aqaba-Eilat Development accords will
be signed by the officials from the two countries.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremonies, the Crown Prince and the Israeli
prime minister are expected to deliver speeches assessing the
peace process and bilateral relations under the peace treaty. They
will also evaluate the importance of the coming phases in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Signed Tuesday was the agreement on transportation which was
widely acclaimed here as the "linchpin" of all the agreements
signed between the two countries because it consolidates many of
the other eight cooperation agreements signed before, including a
trade agreement and an agreement on tourism.
</P>
<P>
The transport agreement permits the transport of goods to the
Palestinian self-rule areas and facilitates the exchange of goods
and tourists between Jordan and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The other bilateral accords already signed includes health and
medicine, energy, environment protection, border crossing points
and combating crime and drugs as well as agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
