<HEADLINE> Kenya, Uganda Vow To Strengthen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi will visit Uganda next week for further talks with his
Ugandan counterpart Yoweri Museveni in a bid to consolidate East
Africa cooperation.
</P>
<P>
President Moi made the announcement soon after meeting with
Museveni this morning in Teso District, western Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from the talks with President Museveni, Moi said from
now on, Kenya and Uganda will work together for the benefit of
the peoples of the two countries and the entire region.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that their meeting opened greater vision for
East African cooperation both economically and politically.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said Uganda on its part will continue to consolidate
the friendly relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders later reiterated their commitment towards the
East Africa cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries deteriorated in 1995
resulting from the crisis in Rwanda and, the presence of Kenyan
guerrillas in Uganda as claimed by the Kenyan government.
</P>
<P>
The Moi-Museveni meeting is believed to have been proposed by
the newly-elected Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda were member states of the defunct
East African Community (EAC) which was collapsed in 1977.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the defunct EAC expressed their desire to
revive the East African cooperation at a meeting in Arusha,
Tanzania,in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
