<HEADLINE> Ciller Says Turkey Tries to Peacefully Settle Ferry Hijacking in Black Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkish caretaker Prime Minister
Tansu Ciller today strongly condemned the violence of the ferry
hijacking in the Black Sea on Turkey's territory and said her
government was trying to settle this incident peacefully.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the CNN, Ciller said that the
Turkish government were working "around o'clock" to watch the
situation that a group of Chechen militants have been hijacking
"Avrasya" ferryboat and taking over 200 Russian and Turkish
passengers as hostages.
</P>
<P>
Two Turkish assault boats have been following the ferryboat,
hijacked Tuesday night in the Black Sea port of Trabzon,
northeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Ciller said: "We have taken all possible measures to prevent
the bloodshed. We want to solve this problem through
persuasion. We will not resort to force unless absolutely be
necessary."
</P>
<P>
"We are in constant touch with the Russian authorities to
inform them all the aspects of our efforts" in a bid to solve the
ferry hijacking peacefully, she added.
</P>
<P>
But Ciller feels that what is happening in Turkey is related to
the Chechen situation.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that it would not have taken place if the Chechen
question had been brought to a peaceful and satisfactory end as
well," she said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has historical and cultural ties with Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
Muhammed Tokcan, leader of the hijackers, said that they would
release the hostages on board when the hijacked ship reaches
Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
However, Ciller pointed out the Turkish government would not
allow the hijacked ferryboat to reach the Bosphorus Strait,
saying that Turkey would persuade the hijackers to stop around
Eregli, about 100 miles east of Istanbul. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
