<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Makes Surprise Interest Rate Cut by 0.25% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of England announced on
Thursday an unexpected cut in its principal interest rate of 0.25
percent to 6.25 percent, the second reduction in two months.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke cited easing
inflationary pressures and sluggish growth as a justification for
the rate cut.
</P>
<P>
He said in a statement the decision was made "in the light of
evidence confirming that inflationary pressures have continued to
ease".
</P>
<P>
"The economy is continuing to grow, but at a rate which is
clearly below trend. Activity has slowed more sharply in many of
our major export markets particularly in Europe, and this is
contributing to slower growth at home." Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
The cut came one day after Bank of England Governor Eddie
George held his regular monthly meeting with Clarke on Wednesday,
and barely five weeks after the last reduction on December 13.
</P>
<P>
The announcement followed the release of economic figures which
showed that high street spending rose 0.4 percent last month, well
below City analysts' predictions of a 0.7 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
The slow economic growth and moderate inflation had made
analysts expected a further cut in interest rate, but few had
expected the cut to come so soon after December's reduction of
0.25%.
</P>
<P>
The move was welcomed by business leaders. "The cut should
underpin a pickup in consumer spending and support business
confidence, which has weakened since the middle of last year,"
said Adair Turner, director general of the Confederation of
British Industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
