<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's 1996 Economic Growth Estimated at 7.3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth in South Korea is
expected to slow to 7.3 percent this year, down from 9.3 percent
in 1995, the National Statistical Office (NSO) said here today.
</P>
<P>
But the current account deficit is expected to shrink by 27
percent from 7.98 billion U.S. dollars to 5.86 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's facilities investment is forecast to rise 8.3
percent this year, down from last year's estimated 20 percent,
the NSO said.
</P>
<P>
Exports of finished goods in 1996 are expected to grow 14.8
percent, down from 33 percent in 1995, while consumer spending
will increase by 7.2 percent, down from last year's 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The NSO forcast that prices of industrial products will remain
stable this year, but consumer prices will continue to increase by
4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit is expected to be 2.53 billion U.S. dollars
and a deficit of 3.3 billion dollars is expected in invisible
trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
