<HEADLINE> Duma's New Speaker Offers Cooperation With Kremlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Communist Gennady Seleznyov, the
new speaker of the Russian parliament's lower house, said today
that he will cooperate with the president and prime minister "in a
constructive way."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the relationship between himself, President Boris
Yeltsin and Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin as "a businesslike
triangle," he said he is obliged to cooperate with the head of
state and government.
</P>
<P>
He said that the information reaching Yeltsin's desk 'is
carefully filtered and for this reason it will be probably
interesting for him to hear the view of not only the house speaker
but also the representatives of the left-wing forces which won the
general elections."
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov was elected Wednesday as speaker of the State Duma
after the Communist Party, led by Gennady Zyuganov, won 157 seats
in the 450-seat Duma elections held last month.
</P>
<P>
The speaker urged the strengthening of economic ties with the
countries of the Commonwealth of Independent States and stressed
the need to tighten legislative sanctions against terrorists in
response to the recent hostage-takings by Chechen militants within
and outside Russia. 
</P>
