<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps Up Petroleum Law Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China is quickening its pace of
drawing up its Petroleum Law, in a bid to ensure the sustained and
sound development of the oil industry through legal means.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior official with the China National
Petroleum Corporation (CNPC), the Chinese government has all along
paid great attention to the drawing up of the petroleum law and
has empowered the CNPC to work out the draft.
</P>
<P>
Over more than one year of survey and study, the CNPC has
worked out the draft and delivered it to the Bureau of Legislative
Affairs of the State Council for examination.
</P>
<P>
He said that for a long time the country's oil sector has been
governed by administrative means, which can not standardize the
relations between oil enterprises and the state as well as other
relevant departments in the exploration and utilization of oil and
gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
The official mentioned that despite the eight specific
administrative rules the country has laid down in administering
the petroleum sector, many aspects of the sector still have no
rules to abide by.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the existing rules and regulations have proved less
efficient and less compatible with the actual situation of the
petroleum sector.
</P>
<P>
The official said that public security is worsening in the
areas near oilfields. The crude oil and related goods and
materials stolen every year in the country's oilfields cause
losses totalling one billion yuan. Oil enterprises lack a safe and
stable production environment, he added.
</P>
<P>
Thus, it is imperative for the country to make a petroleum law
that suits the actual development of the oil industry and matches
international practices, the official stressed.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the petroleum law will be
promulgated at an early date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Women's Organization Calls for More Equality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The equality between men and
women is protected by law and must not be violated, said the title
of a front-page article carried by the "China Women's News"
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In this follow-up story about female college students being
refused jobs by government employers, Chen Muhua, chairperson of
the All-China Women's Federation (ACWF), was quoted as saying that
more policies and laws should be formulated to protect women's
right to work.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who is also vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of
the National People's Congress, asked news media to supervise
ministries and departments, saying that to refuse to employ women
or limit their development is against China's basic policy of
equality between males and females and is against the Law on
Protection of Women's Rights and Interests.
</P>
<P>
ACWF vice-chairperson Huang Qizao was quoted as saying that the
ACWF pays great attention to the problem and is preparing active
countermeasures.
</P>
<P>
The "China Women's News" disclosed on January 8 that 27
ministries and departments had refused to employ or placed limits
on employing female college graduates at a talent exchange fair
held by the Ministry of Personnel over the first weekend this year.
</P>
<P>
Huang reaffirmed that action is and will be taken in realizing
equality between men and women. She said that the Chinese
government has made promises.
</P>
<P>
"Made them, and carried them out too," Huang stressed, asking
departments and units, governmental and non-governmental
organizations to work to keep these promise.
</P>
<P>
State Councillor Peng Peiyun wrote to Minister of Personnel
Song Defu urging him to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
The first female personnel market in China went into operation
recently in Changsha, capital of central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
The market, aiming to give full play to women's talents, has so
far drawn more than 2,000 women to compete for over 800 positions
offered by 50 units. Co-sponsored by the personnel department of
the provincial government and a local company, the personnel
market will provide employment information and handle the
necessary formalities for both job seekers and employers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
