<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Snow Hits Nanjing, but Traffic Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A heavy snowfall seldom seen in
the past decade has changed east China's Nanjing City into an icy
world, where the traffic, however, was reported normal because of
a citywide snow-clearing drive.
</P>
<P>
A cold front from north China brought 10-28 mm of snowfall to
east China from Wednesday morning, including such big cities as
Shanghai, Hangzhou and Wuhan. Data from the meteorological
department of Jiangsu Province showed that it was the heaviest
snowfall since 1984.
</P>
<P>
The city government of Nanjing, capital of Jiangsu, had made a
snow-clearing plan in advance. More than 200,000 government
officials, workers, residents, policemen and soldiers were
involved in sweeping snow this morning. As a result, all major
streets were cleared before 8:00 am.
</P>
<P>
So far, the highway, railway and air traffic here are normal,
and no serious traffic accidents have been reported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
