<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Standardization Urged for Listed Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A senior securities official
said today that the state will continue to standardize listed
companies this year to help establish a modern enterprise system
inside them.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Daojiong, president of the State Securities Supervision
Committee (SSSC), made the remark in this capital city of south
China's Hainan Province at a seminar sponsored by the SSSC and the
State Economic and Trade Commission (SETC).
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that listed companies must operate in accordance
with securities-related laws and regulations, enhance management
of corporate persons, and enable the public to get to know more
about their actual operation conditions.
</P>
<P>
At the same time he called on the country's securities
supervision committees to enhance their supervision of listed
companies to ensure the sound development of the country's
securities market.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou, most of the current 300-plus listed
companies have grown out of state-owned enterprises, and they face
the same plight of many other large- and medium-sized state
businesses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
