<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Explains Delay in Hostage-Freeing Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today said the hostage-freeing operation in Pervomaiskoye took
longer than expected because the Chechen separatists had created a
well-armed stronghold with a warren of underground passages in the
village.
</P>
<P>
"When I said that the operation would take one day, we did not
know that a stronghold of (separatist Chechen leader Dzhokhar)
Dudayev had been created underground (the village) long ago,"
Yeltsin told a news conference today.
</P>
<P>
In the end, it took the Russian forces four days to wipe out
the terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said piles of weapons and underground passages linking
houses in the Dagestani village near the Chechen border had
complicated the situation.
</P>
<P>
The president earlier announced the hostage-freeing operation
has been successfully completed and that all the Chechen militants
in Pervomaiskoye had been killed.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 250 Chechens, headed by Dudayev's son-in-law
Salman Raduyev, sneaked into the Dagestani city of Kizlyar on
January 9 and took more than 3,000 people hostage.
</P>
<P>
The militants were stopped at Pervomaiskoye on their way back
to Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Russian military launched a full-scale attack on
the Chechen militants, but only finally claimed success in wiping
out the separatists on Thursday after pounding the village with
rockets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
