<HEADLINE> Japanese, Pakistan Premiers Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto today urged that the dispute between Pakistan and India
over Kashmir be resolved through peaceful dialogue, Kyodo News
Service reported.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto made the remark during talks with Pakistan's Prime
Minister Benazir Bhutto at his official residence.
</P>
<P>
Bhutto, who arrived here Wednesday for a four-day official
visit, said that Pakistan has long tried to settle the territorial
dispute with India. But India has not responded to her country's
efforts and has refused to put the row on the negotiating table,
the news service quoted her as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto also pledged up to 59.65 billion yen (596.5 million
U.S. dollars) in low-interest loans to Pakistan in fiscal year
1996 to help fund two economic infrastructure improvement
programs, an educational project and an agricultural project.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Bhutto told a group of Japanese business leaders
that her country hopes to bolster its economy by enhancing
cooperation with Japan in information technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
