<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Chechen Militants in Pervomaiskoye Killed: Yeltsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 18 (Xinhua) -- All the Chechen militants in the
Daghestani village of Pervomaiskoye have been killed and the next
target for the federal forces will be the strongholds of the
separatists in Chechnya, Russian President Boris Yeltsin said
today.
</P>
<P>
All the bandits were eliminated, unless they had gone into
hiding underground, said Yeltsin at a news conference held in the
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 250 militants headed by Salman Raduyev, the
son-in-law of separatist Chechen leader Dzhokhar Dudayev, were
trapped in the village on Monday when the Russian special forces
and Interior troops began their hostage-freeing operation.
</P>
<P>
"We taught Dudayev good lesson and now we have to deal a blow
to his strongholds where there is no civilian population in order
to put an end to terrorism on Russian soil," Yeltsin added.
</P>
<P>
He said: "It (terrorism) has already spread to Turkey. This is
already international terrorism. This cannot be tolerated."
</P>
<P>
The president stressed that the hostage-freeing operation was
conducted with "minimal" loss of lives among the civilians and the
federal military.
</P>
<P>
According to Yeltsin, 82 hostages were freed and 18 are
reported missing. The missing were considered alive rather than
dead. The president said: "They could be in hiding or have run
away."
</P>
<P>
He put the Russian military death toll at 26. Two out of the
250 "Alpha" (special forces) commandos were wounded, he said. The
casualty figure came from a report by his Security Minister
Mikhail Barsukov and Interior Minister Anatoly Kulikov.
</P>
<P>
The crisis began on January 9 when Chechen militants stormed
into the Dagestani city of Kizlyar and took over 3,000 people
hostage.
</P>
<P>
After releasing most of hostages, the Chechens were allowed to
leave the city. The separatists, however, were stopped at
Pervomaiskoye not far from the Dagestani-Chechen border on January
10.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Russian special forces and Interior troops,
backed by tanks, artillery and helicopter gunships, launched a
full-scale attack against the Chechen militants holding some 100
hostages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
