<HEADLINE> UN Envoy to Persuade Taliban to Stop Rocketing Kabul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 18 (Xinhua) -- UN special envoy to
Afghanistan Mehmud Mestiri said in Kabul today that he would
persuade Taliban to stop rocketing the Afghan capital.
</P>
<P>
Reports coming from Kabul quoted Mestiri as saying, "I am sure
that Taliban cannot take over Kabul militarily."
</P>
<P>
Taliban wanted to frighten Kabul residents to leave the city,
but there were still 750,000 people living in Kabul, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he admitted that most of the 750,000 residents were
the poor who could not afford to leave.
</P>
<P>
Taliban has been rocketing Kabul off and on since its troops
advanced to the areas only five kilometers away from the southern
district of Kabul on October 21, 1995.
</P>
<P>
Mestiri left here today for Kabul to meet Afghan current
President Burhanuddin Rabbani and his top commander Ahmad Masood
for finalizing a peace formula for the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the UN office in Kabul, Mestiri said that he also
planned to meet Taliban which vows to overthrow the Rabbani
regime.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
