<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "People's Daily" Calls for Curbing of Price Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Effective measures must be
taken in 1996 to rein in price rises and ensure a further drop in
the price growth rate all over the country, the "People's Daily"
says in an editorial to be carried tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of social commodity retail prices dropped on a
monthly basis in 1995 in comparison with the previous year -- from
23.2 percent in December 1994 to 8.3 percent in December last
year. The annual commodity retail price rose by 14.8 percent,
reaching the government's price adjustment and control goal of
about 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
"These achievements demonstrated the ability of the Party and
government to control the macro-economy in shifting to a socialist
market economic system," the editorial says. "They mark the fact
that China's marco-economic environment has further improved, the
economy has maintained a sustained, rapid and healthy momentum,
thus laying a relatively good foundation for the smooth start of
the Ninth Five-year Plan this year."
</P>
<P>
Although a relatively good job was done of controlling and
adjusting prices in 1995, the price growth rate remained rather
high, the editorial points out. It says that the central
government will map out price control targets for the whole
country and individual localities.
</P>
<P>
"Governments at all levels must stick to and improve the
responsibility system concerning price control, earnestly
strengthen the leadership of price-related work and organize
various departments to comprehensively administer price control,"
it says.
</P>
<P>
Properly tight financial and monetary policies should be
observed in the new year, the scale of investment in fixed assets
must be put under strict control, and the over-growth of
consumption funds be curbed, it says. At the same time, efforts
must be made for the development of production and increase of
efficient supply in accordance with the market demand.
</P>
<P>
It notes that down-to-earth efforts must be made in
agriculture, and provincial governors must be responsible for the
grain production and mayors for "vegetable baskets" to ensure the
steady increase of supplies of grain, cotton, edible oil, eggs,
meat and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
"All localities must earnestly work in the spirit of the
central government's working conference on rural work," it
says. "They must take measures to increase input in agriculture,
improve agricultural production conditions and the ability to
resist natural disasters, stabilize the prices of agricultural
production materials, and alleviate the burdens on farmers."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
