<HEADLINE> Rice Production Areas Urged to Increase Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China plans to increase rice
output by 2.5 billion kg every year during the next five years in
order to ensure enough supply of grain to 1.2 billion Chinese
people by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the annual rice output will account for 40 percent
of the total grain output, and there will be an annual average of
150 kg rice available per person, according to a five-year plan
drawn up by the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"There is plenty of potential to tap in rice production in
order to ensure an output of 490 billion kg of grain by the end of
the century," said Agriculture Minister Liu Jiang during a recent
inspection of south China's Hainan Province.
</P>
<P>
As a major rice producing area, south China should increase its
output to 10 billion kg, or 80 percent of the national total
increased output, Liu quoted the plan as saying.
</P>
<P>
Early rice, late rice and ratooning rice will be widely grown,
and high-quality and high-yield rice will continue to be
developed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Liu urged officials at different levels to attach great
importance to rice production and make preferential policies in
this respect.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
