<HEADLINE> Afghan Hekmatyar Group Makes New Peace Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Gulbuddin Hekmatyar, chief of
Afghan Hezb-i-Islami (Hekmatyar Group), today called for
establishing a combined front for peace in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in Peshawar, Pakistan, Hekmatyar
said, "we are ready to hold talks with any Afghan warring
factions if they agree to our proposals."
</P>
<P>
He said that his proposals offered the establishment of an
interim government in Afghanistan, which should be acceptable to
all the factions.
</P>
<P>
The interim government will be responsible for organizing
elections to decide the future government, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that his party had held talks with Taliban in this
regard, but he did not disclose the outcome of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Both Hezb-i-Islami and Taliban are representatives of the
Pushtoo people, the majority of Afghan nationals, but they have
not allied each other so far.
</P>
<P>
Hekmatyar acted as the prime minister of an Afghan coalition
government in 1993 and the leader of four-party opposition
alliance in 1994.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Hekmatyar strongly criticized the
"foreign interference in Afghanistan" and named some of such
countries which supported Afghan current President Burhanuddin
Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his pessimism over the UN peace efforts
launched by the UN special envoy to Afghanistan Mehmud Mestiri.
</P>
<P>
To revive the UN peace mission, Mestiri arrived in Islamabad
last Friday and went to Kabul to meet Rabbani today.
</P>
<P>
Hekmatyar said, "we have not received any message from Mestiri
concerning the holding of talks."  
</P>
</TEXT>
