<HEADLINE> Li Peng Meets Hong Kong Delegation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said
here today that China has both the confidence and the ability to
ensure the implementation of the principle of "one country, two
systems" in Hong Kong after July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Li made this remark during a meeting with a delegation from the
Better Hong Kong Foundation, which is composed of leading Hong
Kong industrialists including Li Ka-Shing and Tsang Hin Chi, who
are advisors on Hong Kong affairs and members of the Preparatory
Committee of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
Li said that he hoped that after China resumes the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong in 1997, Hong Kong will continue to
maintain its prosperity and stability, as well as its position as
an international financial, trade and shipping center, and
continue to serve as a bridge linking the Chinese mainland with
the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Asked by Li Ka-Shing about the measures the Chinese government
will adopt to guarantee the smooth implementation of the principle
of "one country, two systems" in Hong Kong, Li said that this
principle is a great concept put forward by Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
"Now this has become our country's basic state policy and a
policy of seeking truth from facts by fully taking into
consideration Hong Kong's history and actual situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government has both the confidence and the ability
to carry out this principle in Hong Kong after 1997," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
First, he explained, the Basic Law of the Hong Kong SAR has
been formulated.
</P>
<P>
After the signing of the Sino-British Joint Declaration, he
said, China's National People's Congress (NPC) set up a Drafting
Committee for the Basic Law of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
He said that this important law with historical and
international significance was formulated through more than four
years of effort.
</P>
<P>
A series of Chinese government principles and policies toward
Hong Kong have been fixed by this law, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
