<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK Bourse to Greet 1st H-Share of 1996 (by Chang Kefei) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China's largest textile
machinery manufacturer is making the last dash to go public on the
 Hong Kong Stock Exchange, which will become the first state-owned
 enterprise to issue H-shares in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Jingwei Textile Machinery Company Limited plans to issue a
total of 160 million H-shares, at 1.29 HK dollars per
share. Trading of the shares are expected to begin on February 2,
when the company will be China's 18th state-owned enterprise
listed on the Hong Kong bourse.
</P>
<P>
Public subscription for 40 million stocks will start tomorrow
and last till next Wednesday, and the other 120 million shares
will be offered to institutional investors by way of placing.
</P>
<P>
According to the Hong Kong-based Peregrine Capital Limited --
the sponsor and lead underwriter of the issue, institutional
investors are active in the placing of Jingwei H-shares, which
started this morning.
</P>
<P>
Francis P.T. Leung, chairman of Peregrine said today: "It is
lucky for Jingwei to be listed at this time, when the Hong Kong
stock market shows signs of turning up."
</P>
<P>
Entering into 1996, the stock market has ridden on recovery
thanks to the big inflow of foreign funds, and the daily turnover
has stayed high. Prices of H-shares, indicating the performance of
 17 China's state enterprises already listed at the Hong Kong
exchange, have rebounded since the end of last December.
</P>
<P>
The bullish atmosphere on the stock market will help the
promotion of the Jingwei shares, said Leung, who also acknowledged
that the textile machinery builder itself has a good quality.
</P>
<P>
Situated in Shanxi in northern China, the 45-year-old Jingwei
company manufactures a wide array of textile machinery and
supplementary components and special parts. Many of its products
take a dominance at the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Mei Zai-sen, chairman of Jingwei company, said here today at a
press conference that through placing and new issue, Jingwei
expects to raise funds of around 200 million HK dollars (25.6
million US dollars), which will be mainly used to purchase
production facilities and technical equipment, and to expand
production capacity.
</P>
<P>
Jingwei is not worried about its domestic market demand though
China's state-owned textile enterprises have been in predicament
due to a chronic lack of funds and piled-up stocks.
</P>
<P>
According to Mei, business volume of the company reached 710
million yuan (84.5 million US dollars) in 1995, which took a small
 stake of the total market demand of the year, estimated at 30
billion yuan (3.6 billion US dollars). Actually, overseas textile
machinery producers took away a large part of the huge cake;
Jingwei, as the leading textile machinery manufacturer in China,
possessed about 10 percent of the market left. Therefore, there is
 still potential market to explore.
</P>
<P>
China now has 50,000 textile enterprises, including 10,000
large and medium-sized ones. "There is always a big demand for
high-quality products," said Mei. At the beginning each year,
Jingwei gets orders for the coming six months.
</P>
<P>
Besides, overseas demand will keep growing in the next five
years, to make up 25 percent of the company's total sales by the
year 2000. Last year exports accounted for 15 percent of its sales.
</P>
<P>
During the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), the Chinese
government will pump 100 billion yuan (11.9 billion US dollars)
into the textile industry, with 40 billion yuan (4.8 billion US
dollars) earmarked for technical renovations. It is good news for
textile machinery manufacturers, said Mei.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
