<HEADLINE> Japan's Ruling, Opposition Parties Hold Conventions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan's new Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto told his Liberal Democratic Party annual
convention Thursday it should aim to win back its outright
majority at the next general election.
</P>
<P>
The LDP, currently the dominant party in the three-party
coalition government, lost its majority for the first time in four
decades at the last election in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's speech came a week after the LDP took back the
premiership after a lapse of two and a half years, following the
resignation of Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama, leader of the
ruling coalition's Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, who is the LDP president, was quoted by the
Kyodo News Service as saying at the assembly that the ruling
party's top priority is to put Japan's economy back on track.
</P>
<P>
He pledged to restore the country's economy by the beginning of
the 21st century with thorough economic and labor reforms.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto also pledged openness of information and
clarification of responsibility of those trying to win public
support for the controversial government scheme to use 685 billion
yen (6.85 billion U.S. dollars) of taxpayers' money to liquidate
seven troubled housing loan companies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the leading opposition party Shinshinto (New
Frontier Party) Thursday held its second convention since a
December 1994 merger with nine opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
Shinshinto President Ichiro Ozawa, elected as party leader last
month, told the assembly he was determined to press the government
to dissolve the lower house for a snap election, Kyodo said.
</P>
<P>
The news service said that Ozawa denounced the government's
liquidation plan, saying it reflected the lack of political
responsibility and capability of former Prime Minister Tomiichi
Murayama.
</P>
<P>
The liquidation plan was included in the fiscal 1996 budget
drawn up last December by Murayama's cabinet which resigned en
masse earlier this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
