<HEADLINE> Inter-Korean Trade Increases in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Inter-Korean trade increased by
31.1 percent to reach 299 million U.S. dollars last year, the
National Unification Board (NUB) said here today.
</P>
<P>
Trade between South Korea and the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) totaled 228 million U.S. dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The 1995 total volume breaks down to 228 million U.S. dollars
worth of DPRK commodities exported to South Korea and 71 million U.S.
dollars worth of South Korean items exported to the DPRK,
according to the " '95 Trends in Inter-Korean Trade," according to
the NUB.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's exports to the DPRK in 1995 represented a
180-percent increase over 1994 and the import-export ratio was
reduced from 8:1 in 1994 to 3.2:1.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of items traded also increased from 142
in 1994 to 200 in 1995, while the number of firms involved in
trading increased from 160 to 208.
</P>
<P>
Processing-on-commission trade, which began in 1991, registered
26 million U.S. dollars last year, up 56.9 percent over the previous
year. Items handled in the trade, which in the past consisted mainly
of clothes and footwear, expanded to include color TV sets and loud
speakers.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the South Korean government approved a direct
investment proposal made by Daewoo Business Group and permitted
six other enterprises to conduct business activities in the DPRK,
but none of these plans have been materialized so far.
</P>
<P>
"Unless tensions between the North (DPRK) and the South (the
Republic of Korea) worsen, we will continue to gradually expand
economic cooperation with the North," a NUB official said.
</P>
<P>
Since the South Korean government took steps for economic opening
towards the DRPK in 1988, inter-Korean trade amounted to 1.11
billion U.S. dollars by the end of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Force Opens Airports to Civilian Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese air force has
opened 71 military airports and more than 460 military air routes
to civilian air services and offered 53 reserve airports to
civilian airplanes since 1990.
</P>
<P>
China's civil aviation industry has been developing rapidly
over the past few years, but the shortage and unbalanced
distribution of airports has emerged as a bottleneck.
</P>
<P>
To help solve the problem, the air force has in addition closed
180 military training aerial areas and adjusted the locations of
over 300 aerial training areas, according to military authorities.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years the air force has helped 21 provinces
and autonomous regions open civilian air services in remote areas,
handled some 40,000 civilian flights, and transported 2.9 million
tourists and more than 300,000 tons of cargo.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the air force has participated in aerial
prospecting, planting of forests, insecticide spraying, artificial
precipitation, scientific research test flights and rescue work,
military sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
