<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ousted S.leonean Leader Accused Of Attempting To Cling To Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A senior Sierra Leonean
offical today accused former Head of State Valentine Strasser
of "manifesting a very serious intention to succeed himself as
head of state after the February 26 general elections".
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference at the defense headquarters,
Director of Defense Information Karefa Kargbo said: "If this had
succeeded, it would have been a recipe for chaos."
</P>
<P>
Giving a background to events which led to Strasser being
replaced by his deputy, Brigadier Julius Maada Bio, Kargbo said
the Supreme Military Council twice opposed Captain Strasser's
attempt to promulgate a presidential decree which would have
"lowered the age of presidential aspirants from 40 years to 30".
</P>
<P>
"We decided to keep the age at 40 and the decree was passed,"
Kargbo said.
</P>
<P>
Strasser, 29, came to power in an April 1922 coup. Reports
said Strasser and his wife arrived in Conakry, Guinea, on Tuesday
following the palace coup.
</P>
<P>
Kargbo said Strasser had called on the presidential candidate
of the National Unity Party "to step down as he would want to
lead the party".
</P>
<P>
"On Tuesday, we decided that we needed a change in leadership
and Strasser was informed and Brigadier Bio was chosen to replace
him," Kargbo said.
</P>
<P>
He said the February 26 elections "will bring Sierra Leone
into an era of peace", stressing that the military government
"will not align itself with any contesting political party".
</P>
<P>
The elections were pledged mid last year by Strasser as a way
to end the civil war, which was started by the Revolutionary
United Front (RUF) in 1991. The civil war has wrecked Sierra
Leone's mining-based economy and driven more than a third of the
country's four million people from their homes.
</P>
<P>
Kargbo stressed that the army had increased its security
measures to ensure a peaceful election and called on the RUF "to
change his mind not to disrupt the elections.''
</P>
<P>
He said the government had already signed a decree for the
proclamation of elections to be held on February 26.
</P>
<P>
In a broadcast to the nation after being sworn in as the new
head of state yesterday, Brigadier Bio appealed to RUF leader
Foday Sankoh to hold dialogue with the new government and
"formally present his case for our people and the international
community to hear". 
</P>
</TEXT>
