<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lu Ping Meets Hong Kong Delegation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the issue of the legal system, Lu said both the interior and
Hong Kong should steadily improve it and act accordingly.
</P>
<P>
He said that after 1997 Hong Kong is sure to be an area with a
legal system. Therefore, all the people from the interior and the
Chinese-funded institutions there must comply with the law of Hong
Kong. The military forces stationed in Hong Kong will also be
required to abide by the law of the SAR, besides the national laws.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the Basic Law is not merely limited to Hong
Kong, but of nationwide significance, adding that all people and
all cities and provinces of the interior must also abide by it
when handling affairs involving Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The main task of the Preparatory Committee of the Hong Kong SAR
is to make preparations for and organize the SAR government as
well as handle the relevant affairs, including the forming of the
first SAR government, legislature, judicial institutions and
regional organizations, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
In solving the issue of Hong Kong, he said, The Chinese side
will adhere to the principle of "taking ourselves as the mainstay"
and strive to get co-operation from the British side while
catering to the Hong Kong people and relying on them. "However, we
cannot pin our hopes entirely on the British side," he added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong"
means that the permanent Hong Kong residents will govern Hong
Kong, whereas "a high-degree of autonomy" has already been
embodied in the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
He said the "political reform program" introduced by the
British Hong Kong authorities unilaterally sabotaged the "through
train".
</P>
<P>
In view of many issues concerned with the transfer of power
that need to be legislated, it is imperative to form the
legislature, he noted, but there will be some restrictions on its
authority.
</P>
<P>
After the officials to be appointed are in place, Lu said, they
will set out to do some preparation work for a working institution
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
The scale of the institution will hinge on how well the British
side co-operates, he said. If the two sides co-operate properly
the institution will be a smaller one; otherwise, a larger one
will be formed.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that no matter how large the institution is it will
be entirely composed of Hong Kong people, without a single
official from the interior.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office will remain a body under
the State Council, which takes charge of Hong Kong and Macao
affairs, and its principal task is to make the Basic Law
implemented to the letter in Hong Kong, Lu Ping said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
