<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lu Ping Meets Hong Kong Delegation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Lu Ping, director of the Hong
Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the State Council, said here
today that the policy of "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong"
and "a high degree of autonomy" is in no way an expedient measure,
but it will help maintain the prosperity and stability of Hong
Kong and benefit the whole country as well.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with a delegation from the Better Hong Kong
Foundation, which is composed of well-known Hong Kong
industrialists including Li Ka-Shing and Tsang Hin Chi, he said
that there will never be another power above the Hong Kong SAR
government after 1997, and the guideline of "one country, two
systems" will be firmly carried out.
</P>
<P>
He said it is groundless to take a pessimistic view about Hong
Kong's future, adding that both the people and the funds that have
moved abroad are welcome to return to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the issue of permanent Hong Kong residents, he
said that the permanent residents include Chinese citizens and
non-Chinese citizens, according to the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The Preliminary Working Committee (PWC) of the Preparatory
Committee for the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
has agreed that Hong Kong permanent residents with Chinese
citizenship will retain their status as permanent residents if
they return to Hong Kong before 1997; those to return with foreign
citizenship after 1997 can enter Hong Kong and reside and work
there without the need to get visas.
</P>
<P>
He added that China will handle the issue in a lenient way if
it is incorporated into the Basic Law and the Nationality Law of
the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Hong Kong SAR passport is available only to
permanent Hong Kong residents with Chinese citizenship, noting
that the passport can only be issued by the Hong Kong SAR
immigration department, with no other department in hinterland
involved and nobody from the interior able to obtain it through
any other channel.
</P>
<P>
In the case of loss of a Hong Kong passport, Lu said, a new one
may be obtained from a Chinese embassy or consulate abroad, but
the applicant's personal data must be verified by the Hong Kong
SAR immigration department.
</P>
<P>
He said that after obtaining an SAR passport in 1997 Hong Kong
people can maintain their CI, which is effective for traveling
abroad, together with the BN (O) and SAR passports. In short, this
is to provide convenience for Hong Kong people, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
