<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK Property Market Expects Bottoming Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's property market
is showing signs of recovery from the dismal buying sentiment
which started in mid-1994.
</P>
<P>
In the first days of the new year, response to the forthcoming
sale of new apartments was fairly encouraging and official sources
 claimed that results of recent government land auctions are quite
 satisfactory as well.
</P>
<P>
People from the property circles believed that property prices
had bottomed out and an improvement in the market is expected this
 year. Many developers even suggested that it's time for both
sellers and buyers to take action.
</P>
<P>
Analysts from the Vickers Ballas Investment Research attributed
 the improvement to better lending terms, improved affordability,
tight property supply and favorable demographics.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's property prices experienced years of upward
climbing and peaked in early 1994. But since mid-1994, when the
local government adopted restrictive measures, the property market
 began to plunge sharply and continuously.
</P>
<P>
Data show that prices for new flats averaging around 1,000
square feet in size have dropped from the peak level of 10,000 HK
dollars per sq.f. to less than 6,000 HK dollars. Prices for
secondary market have also declined from 10 to 15 percent on
average.
</P>
<P>
The downturn gradually stopped at the end of last year when
many developers abstained from cutting prices further, predicting
that the property market would stabilize or even recover at the
beginning of the new year.
</P>
<P>
Recent transactions in the property market have proven this to
be true.
</P>
<P>
Wheelock Properties lifted the list price of its Parc Royale
development by 10 percent on Wednesday, while Cheung Kong Holdings
 reported that its latest group of 64 flats was 3.7 times
oversubscribed on the second day of registration. Other large
developers said that they will continue to raise list prices for
new developments in the near-term.
</P>
<P>
Cheung Kong said it will release more flats this week to meet
the growing demand, for which the list price will be increased.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts predicted that this year the property transaction
 volume will increase some 30 percent and the prices will also
rise 10 to 15 percent, while some more cautious ones held that
the property market will stabilize but prices will not increase
much.
</P>
<P>
Many developers held that the bullish sentiment of the property
 indices in the stock market is a clear evidence of the recovery
in the property market.
</P>
<P>
Led by property stocks, the local bourse began a major rally at
 the end of 1995, with the Hang Seng Index breaking the
10,000-point barrier on the last trading day, and continued its
gaining mood so far this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
