<HEADLINE> 95 Percent of LD Salons Closed in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China has closed some 95
percent of all commercial laser disc (LDs) salons within 15 days.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 5,000 LD salons across the country have closed
their doors since the government began, on January 1 this year, to
ban the commercial showing of feature film compact discs (CDs) and
LDs in an effort to bring an end to rampant infringement upon
copyrights in this field and eradicate pornographic publications.
</P>
<P>
Wang Wenyuan, a Ministry of Culture official, said that 20
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions have completely
banned the commercial showing of LDs. Ten other provinces have
closed most of their commercial LD salons.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that provincial regulations were mapped out soon
after the Ministry of Culture and the Ministry of Radio, Film and
Television asked to ban the commercial showing of LDs.
</P>
<P>
Due to positive teamwork among and joint efforts from relevant
departments, the banning work has been done very efficiently and
within a short period of time, the official said.
</P>
<P>
"We've achieved what was expected," he said.
</P>
<P>
The work will be continued to bring about a regulated market of
good-quality and non-pirated CDs and LDs. The relevant departments
have decided to set up four audio and video publication markets in
Beijing, Guangzhou, Shanghai and central China's Wuhan City,
respectively, to eradicate piracy of video and audio materials and
the spread of pornography.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
