<HEADLINE> Former Cyprus Government Spokesman Jailed for Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Former government spokesman
Akis Fantis was sentenced to 18 months' imprisonment today by
Nicosia District Court for fraud.
</P>
<P>
A second accused facing the same charges, Charalambos
Socratous Charalambous, was jailed for 14 months.
</P>
<P>
Fantis and Charalambous, who is a businessman, were found
guilty on 16 counts of fraud, conspiracy to commit a crime, abuse
of trust and receiving money under false pretences during Fantis'
term in office.
</P>
<P>
Fantis was appointed government spokesman in 1988 by former
President George Vassiliou and resigned in November 1992, when a
House of Representatives committee launched an investigation into
allegations of mishandling of public money from the enlightenment
fund.
</P>
<P>
The amount misappropriated is estimated at 85,000 Cyprus
pounds (around 170,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
During his term in office, Fantis was chairman of a commission
administering funds aimed to project the views of the government
on the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Reading the sentence, Judge Georgios Aresti said Fantis
misused the trust former Cyprus President Vassiliou showed in him
while Charalambous exploited the high ranking post Fantis had in
the public domain.
</P>
<P>
"In this case, the sentence must serve as a general
deterrent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fantis' defense lawyer Kikis Talarides said he would consult
with his client to decide on an appeal against the conviction and
the sentence which were passed today. Should such an appeal
be successful, Fantis will be freed, he explained.
</P>
<P>
The defense lawyer has 10 days to appeal against the
conviction or the sentence from the date the conviction was
announced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
