<HEADLINE> NATO General Optimistic Over Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, January 18 (Xinhua)-- The Commander of NATO's
operations in Bosnia, General George Joulwan, expressed optimism
regarding the prospects for peace in Bosnia, said today's Swedish
newspaper "Dagens Nyheter."
</P>
<P>
The former enemies in the war are supposed to have
withdrawn completely to their respective sides of the cease-fire
line laid down in the peace agreement by Friday under NATO
supervision, the paper quoted Joulwan as saying in an interview.
</P>
<P>
The North Atlantic Treaty Organization has sent a 60,000-strong
force to Bosnia to implement the Bosnia peace agreement signed in
Paris in December.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. General described enforcing the withdrawal as a
gigantic task. But he is optimistic since all parties involved
have shown signs of willingness to observe the agreement. 
