<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Travel Programs Launched In Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Five new travel programs
launched by tourism authorities in northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region has been packaged into a promotion drive
sponsored by China National Tourism Administration (CNTA).
</P>
<P>
Specially designed for '96 China Holiday, the new itineraries
include floating on the Yarkant, Tarim and Hotan rivers, hunting
in the Altun Mountains, snow skiing on the Nanshan Hill near
Urumqi, the provincial capital, touring along the ancient Silk
Road by car, and making expeditions in the forests around Lake
Hanas.
</P>
<P>
The Tarim River is China's longest inland river, with Yarkant
and Hotan rivers as two tributaries on the upper reaches of the
Tarim.
</P>
<P>
The 2,000-km-long river flows from the west to the east at the
north of the Tarim Basin, and its middle and lower reaches running
through the northern rim of the Taklimakan Desert. With all the
rapids in them, the rivers are ideal for floating.
</P>
<P>
The Altun Mountains are a rare wildlife habitat on plateau
worldwide, with more than 140 precious species living here. An
international hunting ground with a total area of 100 sq km has
started service on the west of the mountains.
</P>
<P>
Starting this year, tourists can hunt five animals such as wild
yaks, blue sheep and argali from March 20 to April 20, or from
September 15 to November 15.
</P>
<P>
The Nanshan scenic area, 60 km from Urumqi, is an ideal place
for snow skiing, and an international skiing ground is to be built
on a large slope in the area.
</P>
<P>
A section of over 5,000 km of the ancient Silk Road runs
through Xinjiang. A car travel will take tourists to numerous
ruins of ancient cities, where they can have a glimpse of the
world's ancient cultures, religions and the folk customs of
various ethnic groups of central Asia.
</P>
<P>
Lake Hanas, still to be developed, is regarded by industrial
experts as a world-class tourism zone. The lake area boasts of
precious trees such as Siberia larches, Korean pines, dragon
spruces and firs.
</P>
<P>
Ren Xizhong, vice director of the regional tourism bureau, said
the bureau and its subsidiaries have dispatched special personnel
to the tourism areas to supervise the quality of tour services and
ensure the safety of both domestic and overseas travelers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Manila to Encourage Dispersal of Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
establish two pilot "nucleus estates" within the year in a bid to
encourage the dispersal of industries outside the capital.
</P>
<P>
According to the Board of Investments (BOI), the projects,
eligible to receive a package of fiscal and tax incentives, will
serve as "magnet centers" in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
Senior BOI officials today invited interested investors to
submit their project proposals for consideration.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Undersecretary Melito Salazar noted, "to
attract major investors in the countryside, we will need to
provide not just industrial estates but housing, medical,
educational and recreational facilities, retirement villages and
commercial areas,"
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors, particularly the Japanese, have complained
that there were no residential villages, hospitals or recreational
parks near certain industrial parks in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
Modeled after "townships" in Malaysia, the proposed industrial
communities will be established in partnership with local
government units. Each township is estimated to cover an area of
over 100 hectares.
</P>
<P>
The Japan International Cooperation Agency has agreed to
undertake a feasibility study to identify sites for the proposed
industrial communities.
</P>
<P>
According to Salazar, the "technopolis" must be established
close to ports and proposed growth areas far from urban centers,
such as those in northern Luzon and Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
An inter-agency committee currently drafting the investment
priorities plan for 1996 includes the setting up of a
"technopolis," hospitals and technical institutes as among the
priority areas for investment.
</P>
<P>
Projects in preferred areas are entitled to a package of
incentives, including a six-year income tax holiday, duty-free
importation of capital equipment and tax credit on domestic
capital equipment.
</P>
<P>
The 1995 investment priority project (IPP) includes 43 priority
investment areas, compared with 66 in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Among these sectors are shipbuilding and ship repair, mass
transport, precision engineering and mining.  
</P>
</TEXT>
