<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Has No Hand In S. Leone's Coup, Says Defence Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian soldiers in Sierra Leone
have no hands in the overthrow of that country's leader,
Captain Valentine Strasser, said Nigerian defence spokesman
Frederick Chijuka.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to newsmen here yesterday, Chijuka said that the change
of leadership in Sierra Leone was that country's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Nigeria believes in the sovereignty of every
nation in the continent, Nigeria is not like some nations which
are always concerned about interfering in the internal affairs
of other sovereign nations."
</P>
<P>
Chijuka described as "unfair and wicked" accusations that
Nigerian soldiers may have master-minded the palace coup in
Sierra Leone on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
His defence was triggered by hearsay that Nigeria may have
influenced Strasser's ousting, following Abuja's
disenchantment with his anti-Nigeria stance at the November
summit of the Commonwealth in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, Nigeria was suspended from the membership of the
world body over the November 10 hanging of nine Ogoni activists
for murder in south Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
As per a memorandum of understanding between the two countries,
Nigeria now has less than a battalion soldiers in Sierra
Leone, helping to protect that country's major public installations
and less than 100 men to train Sierra Leonean army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
