<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Spokesman on Supervision of Foreign Wire Services for Economic Information (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After taking over the management of foreign economic
information release, Xinhua News Agency will discuss with foreign
wire services and their information organs about releasing
economic information with more advanced technology, so as to raise
the timeliness and reliability of the information, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign wire services and their subsidiary information organs
are not allowed to directly recruit economic information
subscribers within China. The spokesman said this means
foreign wire services and their subsidiary information organs can
not sign agreements directly with clients, and vice versa. The
Xinhua New Agency will universally sign agreements with approved
foreign wire services and their subsidiary information organs
about releasing economic information in China.
</P>
<P>
Clients in China who want to obtain economic information from
foreign wire services can go through the necessary formalities at
Xinhua News Agency. "This will not affect client expansion of
foreign wire services," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua will hold business talks with foreign wire services and
their subsidiary information organs to decide the fees for
different types of information in China. The charging will be
justified, which means clients in China will pay reasonable fees
while foreign wire services and their subsidiary organs can get
appropriate profits, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He added that he believed that Xinhua, based on its good
co-operative relations on news exchanges with nearly 100 foreign
wire services, will develop new co-operation with them in terms of
spreading economic information, such as increasing the number of
economic information users in China and offering services to the
users. Xinhua will soon announce the specific details of the
measures to implement the circular issued by the General Office of
the State Council.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Further Economic Ties With Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Britain is to set up a branch of
its development arm in Cuba to boost bilateral economic relations
despite the continuing U.S. economic embargo against the Caribbean
nation.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Development Corporation (CDC), a government
arm for development and finance which operates in more than 50
countries announced the decision today.
</P>
<P>
British companies are already active in sugar harvest
financing, agrochemicals, cigarette manufacturing, investment and
oil exploration in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
But a CDC spokesman said the operation in Cuba would act as a
model and catalyst for future British investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
Electricity, financial services, agriculture and industry are
believed to be promising target sectors.
</P>
<P>
The CDC will hold talks with Cuban government officials over
the next six months to identify sectors in which detailed
investment proposals can be drawn up.
</P>
<P>
British-Cuban relations have been boosted over the past year
and a half through a series of high-level visits as well as an
investment promotion and protection agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
