<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Township Residents Electing New Congress Representatives (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To ensure that every voter can exercise his or her democratic
rights, local People's Congresses at all levels have done
painstaking work.
</P>
<P>
Election meetings are held in constituencies where voters can
easily assemble, while mobile ballot boxes are provided for voters
who have no easy access to the election meetings.
</P>
<P>
The election committee of Maqiu Township in Nanchang County,
Jiangxi Province, set up mobile ballot boxes in Wuhan, capital of
central China's Hubei Province, where 40,000 of the villagers are
working.
</P>
<P>
There are over 600 ships' crew members from the 90th
constituency of Jiangyan Town, Jiangyan County, Jiangsu Province,
working in Zhejiang Province, Shanghai Municipality and southern
parts of Jiangsu.
</P>
<P>
The constituency has sent five groups with mobile ballot boxes
to the ships.
</P>
<P>
A mental patient living in Yongle Village, in northeast China's
Jining Province, was also registered as a voter after his illness
proved to be of an intermittent nature.
</P>
<P>
In order to make sure that candidates are known to the voters,
election committees across China offer timely introductions in
written or oral form.
</P>
<P>
The candidates, however, have also bade farewell to the
traditional Chinese habit of "just doing things without telling
others." They have begun to face the voters directly and canvass
for votes.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Youxiang, director of a woolen mill in Jiangning County,
Jiangsu Province, said, "I think I am responsible and capable
enough to be a spokesman for general public, and can represent the
voters in participating in and discussing political affairs."
</P>
<P>
The City Election Committee of Gao'an City, Jiangxi Province,
asked its candidates to introduce themselves in their
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
The candidates are requested to make speeches on such topics as
"If I were elected, what I would do for the voters?"
</P>
<P>
Chinese law authorizes the representatives of the TPCs at the
grassroots level the following rights: to make decisions on major
political, economic and social issues of their regions, supervise
the daily work of the government and the judicial organs, and
appoint and dismiss government officials of the corresponding
level.
</P>
<P>
With the development of China's construction of democratic
politics and the improvement of the people's democratic and legal
understanding, it is believed, the elections of representatives of
people's congresses at the grassroots level will play an
increasingly important role in China's political life.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Township Residents Electing New Congress Representatives (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- In an outlying village in east
China's Jiangxi Province, more than 300 villagers assembled to
elect the new Township People's Congress (TPC) representatives.
</P>
<P>
A woman called Xu, 82, insisted on voting by herself while
sitting on a bamboo chair on which she was carried to the election
site by her two sons.
</P>
<P>
She said, "It's my right to choose a representative whom I
believe in, and I want someone who really represents us peasants."
</P>
<P>
This is only one scene of many in the ongoing election for new
TPC representatives.
</P>
<P>
Covering 50,000 townships nationwide and involving 760 million
voters, this is the first election held since the amendment to
China's Election Law was made last February.
</P>
<P>
The term for the representatives chosen through the election,
expected to be accomplished by the end of 1996, will be three
years.
</P>
<P>
According to incomplete statistics available from townships
across China, to date, over 90 percent of the voters have turned
out for the election. In addition, about 85 percent of the
candidates for TPC representatives have been jointly nominated by
voters, while the number of candidates nominated by parties and
organizations, which used to account for the bulk of the total, is
now reduced to one sixth of the total.
</P>
<P>
According to an official of the National People's Congress
(NPC) who is in charge of the election, "The changes should be
attributed to the improved awareness of Chinese farmers of the
importance of participating in and discussing political affairs."
</P>
<P>
Wang Xiaohong, 20, a woman worker in a garment factory in
Jiujiang City, Jiangxi Province, said, "I will vote for a
candidate who has education and can help us all become well-off."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
