<HEADLINE> At Least 9 Die in German Foreigner Hostel Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- At least nine people, including
three children, died today in a fire in a hostel for asylum
seekers in northern Germany, police said.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 others were injured and several people are still
missing in the worst arson attack yet against asylum-seeking
foreigners in the country.
</P>
<P>
Firemen would not rule out the possibility of finding more
deaths as they dug into the debris of the hostel in the port city
of Luebeck.
</P>
<P>
Police have already detained two men suspected of arson. The
two, from Mecklenburg-Vorpommern in eastern Germany, were caught
100 meters from the burning hostel which housed asylum seekers
from Africa, Asia and Middle East.
</P>
<P>
It took 110 firemen several hours to control the fire which
spread throughout the four-storey building early in the morning.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners have been the main target of a three-year wave of
violence by German far-right extremists in which at least 30
people have died. On November 23, 1993, three Turkish women died
in an arson attack near Luebeck. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
