<HEADLINE> Mubarak Meets with Gaddafi near Egyptian-Libyan Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
met with Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi this afternoon at a
military base at Sidi Barrani, some 80 kilometers east of the
Egyptian-Libyan border.
</P>
<P>
Because of the air ban, Gaddafi traveled by land to Egypt
earlier today on his first visit to the neighboring country since
January 1995.
</P>
<P>
The libyan leader first arrived in the Egyptian border town of
Saloum and then was accompanied by Egyptian Information Minister
Safwat el-Sherif to Sidi Barrani in the western desert, the
official Middle East News Agency (MENA) said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Gaddafi were expected to discuss bilateral ties,
the latest developments of the Libya-West crisis and a number of
other issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed air, arms and diplomatic embargo on
Libya in April 1992 after Libya refused to comply with a Western
demand for extraditing two Libyan nationals, who were suspected of
bombing a Pan Am passenger plane over Lockerbie, Scotland, in
1988. A total of 270 people were killed in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain insist that the suspects be tried
in the U.S. or Britain while Libya insists that they be tried in a
neutral country or in the International Court of Justice in the
Hague.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports, Gaddafi will also brief
Mubarak on the current situation in the Arab Maghreb Union (AMU)
and the ongoing efforts to contain the present crisis between
Algeria and Morocco in the wake of the latter's decision to freeze
its membership in the AMU.
</P>
<P>
The Arab Maghreb Union groups Algeria, Libya, Mauritania,
Morocco and Tunisia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
