<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Canada Agree to Strengthen Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad and visiting Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien today expressed their wish to further develop economic
and trade ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting this evening, Mahathir told his Canadian
counterpart that Malaysia would like to provide ample room for
Canadian investment and was considering Canada's participation in
a hydro-electricity project in Sarawak.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Ministry Deputy secretary-general Abdul Halim
Ali told the press after the official meeting between Mahathir and
Chretien that Canada could make available its expertise in the
laying of high voltage submarine cables for a distance of 960-km
from Sarawak to Peninsular Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
According to Abdul Halim Ali, Chretien expressed the hope that
Canada would like to participate in infrastructure projects in
Malaysia, but he also wanted Malaysia to import more Canadian
products including transport equipment.
</P>
<P>
Chretien arrived here this afternoon for a two-day official
visit to Malaysia at the invitation of Mahathir to strengthen
trade and political links between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Tomorrow, Chretien and Mahathir will address a plenary session
of Malaysia-Canada Business Leaders Dialogue held here. Chretien
will leave here for Tokyo tomorrow afternoon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
