<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Ex-generals Arrested in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 18 (Xinhua) - South Korean prosecutors
have arrested five retired military generals over the 1979
coup headed by former president Chun Doo-Hwan and the
subsequent massacre of pro-democracy protestors in Kwangju.
</P>
<P>
The five generals arrested early Thursday are Yoo Hak-Seung,
Hwang Yung-Si, Lee Hak-Bong, Chang Sae-Dong and Choi Sae-Chang.
</P>
<P>
The Seoul District Criminal Court approved their arrest on
mutiny charges relating to the 1979 coup and the 1980 suppression
of pro-democracy demonstrations in the southern city of Kwangju in
which more than 200 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
They were the first former army officers to be arrested in
connection with the coup, which ex-president Chun is charged with
masterminding.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Chun has appealed to the Seoul District Criminal
Court, challenging the legality of a special law passed by the
South Korean parliament last month to allow him and his former
aides to be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
Chun claims the law violates the constitutional prohibition of
retroactive legislation.
</P>
<P>
The law cleared the way for the prosecution of Chun and his
colleagues by extending the time limit for their prosecution.
</P>
<P>
As well as indictments over the coup and the Kwangju massacre,
Chun also faces corruption charges for amassing a 910 million
U.S. dollar slush fund while in office between 1980 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
His presidential successor and mutiny coconspirator, Roh Tae-Woo,
is already on trial on charges of accepting bribes from business
tycoons.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors on Wednesday said they will also soon seek arrest
warrants for four or five other men in connection with the coup,
including four incumbent lawmakers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
