<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Urges Further Reform of Light Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo
called for further reform of light industry at a recent national
work conference on the sector held here, so as to meet the
public's growing demands.
</P>
<P>
Wu said the sector maintained a 12 to 13 percent increase rate
of output value during the period 1991-1995, with its export value
exceeding 40 billion US dollars last year, and the output of
certain products ranking among the first in the world.
</P>
<P>
Most enterprises in the sector are small-sized and belong to
the collective economy, Wu said. They have made substantial
progress in market-oriented reforms. The large enterprise groups
have also played a leading role in the sector's development.
</P>
<P>
Creating brand names with nationwide reputations is one of the
effective measures to increase the variety and quality of the
sector's products, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that light industry should strive to explore the huge
potential of the rural market, while attaching the same importance
to consolidating the urban and overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises with nationwide reputations in the eastern part of
China are also encouraged to join hands in production with their
counterparts in the country's middle and western regions, in order
to speed up the development of these localities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
