<HEADLINE> Forest Tour Programs Promoted in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Luntai Park is one of the 22
forest parks in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region since the
remote northwest China region started to build forest parks in
1992 as a new tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
Located at the northern fringe of the Taklimakan Desert, the
park has an alluvial lake with poplars around it, inhibited by
swans, red deers and other wildlife.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to easy access to the park with the completion of a
522-km-long Tarim desert, Luntai Forest Park has been attracting
more and more travelers.
</P>
<P>
China's largest autonomous region, Xinjiang boasts of large
expanses of deserts and rolling mountains, which are strewn with
forests and rare animal and plant species. These, along with the
region's unique ethnic folk culture, have made Xinjiang one of the
most popular tourist regions in China over recent years.
</P>
<P>
Forest tourist programs, including grasslands and desert
expeditions, have become a key part of the development strategy of
Xinjiang's its tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
The parks have provided new job opportunities for local ethnic
minority herdsmen, who treat travelers to folk singing and dancing
as well as handicrafts.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth has also made an increasing number of local
forest tour fans. Statistics show more than 600,000 travelers
visited the forests in Xinjiang in 1995, and the figure is
expected to grow to 10 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the healthy development of forest tour in the future,
local forestry departments draw up regulations to preserve the
forests' ecological environment, besides their routine work of
preventing forest fires and cleaning away garbages left by the
travelers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
