<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch Exam System for Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China is preparing to launch
its first nationwide qualification examination for teachers and
would-be teachers next year.
</P>
<P>
Any of the 10 million-plus people who are teachers currently
may be dismissed if he or she does not pass the exam.
</P>
<P>
The State Education Commission (SEC) is working on the rules of
the examination, and it has just issued a set of interim measures
concerned with recognizing requisite qualifications of teachers.
</P>
<P>
The SEC stated that a teacher would not be given credentials if
he or she could not discharge his or her obligation and did not
pass the exam.
</P>
<P>
China announced the Qualification Rules for Teachers last
month, which is considered an important step to perfect China's
legal framework for education.
</P>
<P>
This is the third professional qualification rule made by the
Chinese government. The other two are related to lawyers and
registered accountants.
</P>
<P>
To improve the quality of teaching is one of the determinations
of the Chinese government as the 21st century approaches.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics issued by the SEC, only eight percent
of all college teachers, 40 percent of all senior middle-school
teachers, 36 percent of all junior middle-school teachers and 13
percent of all elementary-school teachers are qualified.
</P>
<P>
According to the Teachers Law, college teachers should
have received four years of college education or graduate school
education. High-school teachers should have received at least two
years of college education.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, teaching is becoming a more popular profession in
China as the government is promoting the idea of respecting
teachers and improving their treatment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
