<HEADLINE> Israeli-Jordanian Ties to Be Further Boosted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli diplomat said here
that the Jordanian-Israeli relations will be boosted after the two
countries signed the last part of bilateral agreements in Jordan's
Red Sea port city of Aqaba today.
</P>
<P>
Shalom Tourgeman, spokesman for Embassy of Israel in Jordan,
told Xinhua this morning in a telephone interview that following
the conclusion of all agreements required in the Jordanian-Israeli
peace treaty, the two countries will implement all the accords
and strengthen their cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the development of bilateral relations
during the past year, he said: "It is getting better and better."
</P>
<P>
On King Hussein's visit to Israel on January 10, he said
the visit expressed Jordan's aspiration to peace with Israel and
Israelis' admiration of the King as a King of peace-makers.
</P>
<P>
The visit indicates that Israel welcomes more and more Arab
leaders to visit the Jewish State, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Tourgeman said that no one can force others to make peace and
one cannot expect a nation that suffered a lot from conflicts will
forget the phantoms of wars "in one day or a year," a reference to
the opposition by some Jordanians against the normalization with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
It is normal that there are some Jordanians who oppose peace,
he said. 
</P>
