<HEADLINE> Tax Revenue up 31 Percent Annually in Booming Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The industrial and commercial
tax revenue of south China's booming Guangdong Province recorded
an annual rise of 31 percent during the 1991-1995 period to an
aggregated 198.3 billion yuan (about 23.9 billion US dollars) for
the five years.
</P>
<P>
The provincial tax revenue has been the largest among all
provinces since 1992, according to an official source, who said
that tax authorities uncovered 152,200 tax evasion cases worth
3.317 billion yuan in unpaid tax and fines between 1991 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of last year, the state tax bureau alone
recouped 870 million yuan in repaid tax and fines from a total of
6,627 cases of tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong's tax revenue, which first topped the mark of 50
billion yuan in 1994, has been growing by more than 10 billion
yuan annually in three consecutive years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
