<HEADLINE> Iran's Top Officials Support Pluralism in Parliament Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen Iranian ministers
have issued a statement in support of the president's call for
pluralism in the upcoming parliamentary elections, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Persian daily Akhbar said that the 16 cabinet ministers signed
a joint letter to Iran's President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani,
calling for a wider participation of different groups in the
Majlis elections slated for March 8.
</P>
<P>
"It would be wrong and unjust if the parliament became a
monopoly of certain groups that represent only a fraction of the
resources of the nation," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Rafsanjani told a meeting of high-ranking
officials that the country had nothing to fear if people with
diverse ideas were elected into the new Majlis.
</P>
<P>
"It would be natural to find people with different political
tastes. We should not be worried about the presence of different
ways of thinking in the parliament," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Some 5,000 candidates will be vying for a total of 270 seats in
the Fifth Parliament.
</P>
<P>
In a televised speech on November 24 last year, Rafsanjani
called for the establishment of a multi-party system, a move
warmly welcomed by the Iranian media.
</P>
<P>
So far, Hizb-e Mardam-e Iran (Iranian People's Party), formed
by pro-Rafsanjani parliamentarian Qassem Sho'leh Sa'di, is the
only party which has declared its formation.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Rafsanjani's call for wider participation
of different groups in the upcoming elections has received the
approval stamp of some of the major political and religious
figures here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
