<HEADLINE> Share Prices Down But Index Up on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Share prices fell on the
Singapore market today, but the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials (STI) index closed higher at 2,396.27, up by 6.21
points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that most of the shares ended lower on
profit-taking, forced selling and some small-scale short-sales.
</P>
<P>
Some traders had a negative view of the market and more selling
came from forced sales, in which brokers sell positions that had
not been paid for, they said.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume was 210.6 million units, valued at
467.67 million Singapore dollars. Declines overwhelmed advances by
322 to 55, which 146 other counters stayed steady.
</P>
<P>
Berjaya Group was the most actively traded counter with a
turnover of 9.92 million shares. Idris had 5.15 million shares
traded, while Mulpha International saw 4.82 million of its shares
changed hands.
</P>
<P>
SBS led the 55 gainers, as it picked up by 65 cents to 8.9
Singapore dollars. Cerebos was next, gaining 40 cents to 11.3
Singapore dollars. SBS Foreign and MAA each put on 30 cents to
11.3 and 6.65 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Airlines, Singapore Press Holdings Foreign and
Samanda shared the top spot of the losers' list, closing 30 cents
lower each at 13.8, 25.4 and 4.16 Singapore dollars respectively.
Thai Pr lost 30 cents to 18 US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
