<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Delegates Back Total Ban on Nuclear Testing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHA-AM, THAILAND, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese delegates have
expressed support for the conclusion of total ban on testing of
nuclear weapons within 1996.
</P>
<P>
At the Fourth Asia Pacific Parliamentary Forum (APPF) annual
meeting, Chinese delegates called for nuclear powers to reach,
through negotiations, a treaty, under which each country
undertakes not to be the first to use of nuclear weapons against
one another, and not using or threatening to use nuclear weapons
against non-nuclear countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation, led by Zhu Liang, Chairman of the
Foreign Affairs Committee of the National People's Congress of
China, stressed that banning nuclear testing is not a final goal,
but an important step to realize the total ban on nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation's position won the understanding and
support of participants during the meeting which opened Monday in
Cha-am, a seaside resort in Petchaburi Province, some 160
kilometers southwest of Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The acceptation today of the Republic of Marshall Islands, the
APPF now groups 24 countries in the Asia Pacific region. Brunei is
an observer to the group.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4th APPF Meeting Calls For Closer Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHA-AM, Thailand, January 18 (Xinhua) -- parliamentarians from
Asia Pacific countries today adopted a joint communique, calling
for further strengthening political, security and economic
cooperation among legislative bodies in the region.
</P>
<P>
The joint communique, issued at the end of the Fourth Asia
Pacific Parliamentary Forum (APPF) annual meeting today,
highlighted a number of resolutions adopted on nuclear weapons
testing, anti-terrorism, anti-drug, protection of women's and
children's rights, environment protection, and legislative
interchanges.
</P>
<P>
The communique urged all participating countries of the APPF to
give their support to the conclusion as soon as possible and no
later than the end of 1996 of a truly comprehensive and
internationally verifiable test ban treaty as an essential step to
prevent nuclear weapon proliferation and attain the ultimate goal
of total elimination of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The communique noted that the problem of terrorism is a
flagrant  violation of human rights and they called for APPF
member countries to make concerted efforts to tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
On environmental issues, the participants at the meeting agreed
that there should be efforts to put an end to the unfair practice
of natural resources exploitation, particularly by countries with
more advanced technologies in countries with less advanced
technologies without due consideration for the environmental
impact from such exploitation, the communique said
</P>
<P>
Regarding social issues, the communique stressed APPF countries
would take appropriate measures to protect women and children from
all forms of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
Expressing serious concern over organized international crimes,
including international drug production, trafficking and
consumption, the communique called for APPF governments and
parliaments to enhance law enforcement structures and capabilities
to tackle these problems.
</P>
<P>
The Republic of Marshall Islands was accepted as the 24th
member of the APPF at today's meeting, while the Philippines and
Peru were elected as new members of the APPF executive committee.
</P>
<P>
Brunei is an observer to the group.
</P>
<P>
The fourth APPF annual meeting opened here Monday and 114
parliamentarians from 24 participating countries (including
Brunei) of the APPF attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The fifth APPF annual meeting will take place in Canada in
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
