<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Deports Indian National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Controversial
businessman in Tanzania, an Indian national, Vidyadhar
Girdharlal Chavda flew out of the country on Tuesday evening
under a deportation order issued earlier that day by Home affairs
Minister Ali Ameir Mohamed.
</P>
<P>
The local press reported here today that a notice from the
Tanzanian immigration services headquarters to Chavda said his
continued presence in Tanzania "is in the opinion of the
President undesirable".
</P>
<P>
Chavda, whose alleged misuse of more than 900 million Tanzanian
Shillings (about 1.5 million US dollars) in the Debt Conversion
Program (DCP) funds has made headlines in the last two years and
prompted a parliamentary probe, "successfully resisted" an
earlier order to leave the country in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The government had declared him persona non grata but was
restrained by the High Court, which ordered that Chavda should
not be deported until the main application challenging the order
was heard. The government withdrew the order in February, last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
