<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Expiration of Nomination Deadline Worsens Political Situation in Bangladesh (by Jiang Xianming) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The political situation in
Bangladesh has been worsening with the passing of the deadline at
05:00 PM Wednesday for filing nomination papers for the upcoming
general elections.
</P>
<P>
All efforts by the political and diplomatic circles appeared
abortive as the ruling party and the opposition in the country
failed to resolve the 21-month-old standoff over the issue of
holding the elections under a neutral caretaker government, local
press said in their comments.
</P>
<P>
"Now we have to go ahead with the elections in the country and
the election rules do not allow us to reverse the proceedings of
the nomination," the Election Commission (EC) said last night,
adding that the EC even did not receive any request from any
political party till 05:00 PM Wednesday to further change the
election schedule.
</P>
<P>
However, in their liaison meeting Wednesday, the three
mainstream opposition parties -- the Awami (people's) League, the
Jatiya (national) Party and the Jamaat-e-Islami -- decided to
boycott the upcoming general elections and resist them at any
cost.
</P>
<P>
The combined opposition no longer demanded polls. "Rather, from
now on, our campaign will be directed towards the formation of a
caretaker government with the fall of the ruling party," an
opposition leader warned.
</P>
<P>
The election schedule was first announced on December 4, fixing
January 18 as the voting date. It was then deferred to February 7.
On January 2, the EC made a partial change in the schedule, fixing
January 8 and 9 as the last dates for filing nomination papers.
Then on January 8, the EC again revised the schedule, fixing
January 17 and 18 as nomination filing and scrutiny dates. The
polls date was shifted to February 15.
</P>
<P>
There were widespread speculation this time that nomination
filing date would be rescheduled once again because there had been
efforts till Tuesday to remove the government-opposition standoff.
</P>
<P>
It was learnt that the ruling Bangladesh Nationalist Party
(BNP) has recently proposed a formula under which the country's
president will head an advisory council to be constituted with
equal representation from both sides and the president will also
enjoy the power of the prime minister. But the opposition
disagreed with the proposal and suggested that there must be a
neutral chief advisor who will enjoy the power of the prime
minister as the head of the caretaker government.
</P>
<P>
Up to now a total of 1,987 nomination papers were filed for the
February 15 elections. Almost all of them are from the BNP
nominees and its dissidents who filed the nomination papers as
independent candidates. All three mainstream opposition parties
have refrained from filing nomination papers.
</P>
<P>
People worried that if the ruling party go ahead with the
elections, the political situation in the country may be more
violent as the opposition has set for all-out agitation.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties have announced that they would siege the
election commission offices throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, six western envoys led by US ambassador David Merrill
mediated between the ruling party and the opposition. Although
they tried in vain to persuade the two sides to reach a consensus,
their efforts may continue.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of continued contacts between the BNP and the
opposition with the mediation of political and diplomatic circles
will not be ruled out, but it may be difficult for the two sides
to heal their quarrels over the power-sharing of the
opposition-demanded caretaker government to conduct the national
elections, analysts here said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
