<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Berlusconi Trial Adjourned until January 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The first day of hearing on the
corruption trial of former Italian Prime Minister Silvio
Berlusconi closed Wednesday, and the next session is to open on
January 26.
</P>
<P>
The trial opened in the morning. Berlusconi appeared in the
Court of Milan stormed by reporters under the accompany of his
lawyer Carlo Taormina.
</P>
<P>
The opening session was adjourned for a while at mid-morning
after judges ruled out live television coverage but allowed video
broadcast.
</P>
<P>
The judges brought down a demand by Taormina that proceedings
of the case be changed.
</P>
<P>
Berlusconi left the court room about 3:40 p.m. before the
hearing ended.
</P>
<P>
The 59-year-old media magnate, his younger brother Paolo and
nine others are charged with corruption over alleged bribes made
by his Fininvest empire to tax police of Milan for easy audits
between 1989 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
But only Berlusconi appeared in court Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Documents provided by detained Francesco Nanocchio, a former
Milan tax policeman, showed that between 1989 and 1992, three
Fininvest companies -- insurer Mediolanum Vita, television
producer Videotime and publisher Mondadori -- had paid a total of
330 million lira (about 206,000 U.S. dollars) to Milan tax police
in three bribes.
</P>
<P>
Berlusconi denied he had been aware of this, saying he was just
an "outsider".
</P>
<P>
In today's hearing, Berlusconi and Taormina claimed the trial
is "for political purposes".
</P>
<P>
The trial has heavy political overtones as the caretaker
government of Lamberto Dini is in crisis after Dini announced
resignation on January 11.
</P>
<P>
Italy has been without an elected government since Berlusconi's
coalition government collapsed in December 1994 only after seven
months in office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
