<HEADLINE> Indian Medical Conference Held in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Sher
Bahadur Deuba today inaugurated an Indian conference of physicians
here in Kathmandu, capital of Nepal, welcoming the Indian doctors
attending the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The 51th general conference of the Association of Physicians of
India (API) was scheduled to discuss regional health problems in
South Asia and work out concrete programs for diagnosis and
treatment for diseases like malaria, AIDS and heart disease
through exchange of experiences in medicine and technology.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 3,000 delegates from India are participating in the
five-day event and the conference was also being attended by
doctors from other South Asian countries like Nepal, Bangladesh,
Sri Lanka and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that the Indian medical organization API
held its annual conference outside India in its history of more
than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Indian Health Minister A.R. Antulay and his Nepali counterpart
Arjun Narsing K.C. were also present at today's inaugural
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
According to Antulay, South Asian countries had agreed recently
to hold similar conference of medical professionals every year on
the regional level from 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
