<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 09:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar tumbled
against major currencies due to unfavorable imports figures
released today.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar slid to 74 US cents from 74.34 US cents
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The downturn of the local currency happened after the
Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) announced that monthly
merchandise imports continued to grow by a robust five percent in
December last year.
</P>
<P>
The imports figures fueled fear that the country's annual
current account deficit might surpass the target of 21 billion
Australian dollars (15.5 billion US dollars) set by the government
for 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
The local currency exchange market responded negatively to the
figures, because it expected only a modest 1.5 percent growth in
imports in the month.
</P>
<P>
The Australia dollar slid neck by neck with the US dollar in
cross rates against the Japanese yen. It ended at 78 yen from
78.97 yen Wednesday, while the US dollar dropped to 105.42 yen
from 106.15 yen on last close in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was also weaker against the German mark,
ending at 1.0857 marks from 1.0908 marks on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Local currency brokers expected the Australian dollar to remain
within the range between 73.85 and 74.25 US cents in overseas
markets in the next 24 hours.  
</P>
</TEXT>
