<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 09:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top 10 Science News Items for 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The acquittal of five
scientists in a lawsuit over the sale of banned rat killer ranked
as the No.1 science story in China for 1995.
</P>
<P>
The selecting of the top 10 stories was done by 397
academicians of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) and Chinese
Academy of Engineering (CAE). Results were announced here today by
Zhu Guangya, chairman of the China Association of Science and
Technology and CAE president.
</P>
<P>
The 10 stories are as follow:
</P>
<P>
(1) Five scientists involved in the "Qiao Mantun Rat Killer
Case" were acquitted and the General Office of the State Council
issued a circular that voiced approval of the destruction of
stocks of the poison.
</P>
<P>
The scientists, who had been convicted in an earlier ruling,
appealed to society not to use rat killer that was developed by a
Mr. Qiao. The poison contained hypertoxic drugs that had been
banned and which are harmful to the environment.
</P>
<P>
(2) The China North Pole expedition arrived at the North Pole
on foot following a 13-day trek.
</P>
<P>
(3) Nearly 100 CAS academicians answered central authorities'
call for the popularization of science and technology.
</P>
<P>
(4) The National Intelligent Computer Institute developed the
Dawn 1000 parallel processing computer with a calculating speed of
1.58 billion bites per second and a storage capacity of 1,024
megabites.
</P>
<P>
(5) National Defense University developed China's first
magnetic suspension train with a speed of 500 km per hour.
</P>
<P>
(6) China revealed its decision to speed up scientific and
technological progress and held a national conference on science
and technology to push its strategy of improving China through
science and technology and education.
</P>
<P>
(7) The 300,000 kw Qingshan nuclear power station, which was
designed and built by China, passed State inspection and produced
5 billion kwh since it went into operation in December 1991.
</P>
<P>
(8) Northwest Agriculture University developed a hybrid spring
wheat with an average per-hectare yield of 6,000 kg, demonstrating
that China is in the forefront of hybrid wheat research in the
world.
</P>
<P>
(9) Forty-one members of the National People's Political
Consultative Conference who are scientists called for an
investigation of financial losses caused by a program that claimed
it could turn water into oil. Natural and social scientists also
called for safeguards in the sciences to fight pseudo-scientific
frauds.
</P>
<P>
(10) Zhejiang Medical University President Mao Jiangsen
developed the world's first hepatitis A vaccine that can prevent
the disease with an injection. China has the capacity to produce
vaccine sufficient for 5 million people annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
