<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 08:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Corruption Team Pointed In Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A nine-man commission
headed by former Premier and first Vice-President Mr. Joseph
Sinde Warioba has been appointed in Tanzania to look into how
best the government and its institutions can fight corruption.
</P>
<P>
President Benjamin Mkapa told a press conference at the State
House in Dar es Salaam on Wednesday that the commission was
expected to report back to him within nine months.
</P>
<P>
He said the commission would collect opinions from
individuals, professional associations and other interest groups
and present a broad, analytical, and open report taking into
account the obtaining situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa identified two strategies on how to fight corruption.
The first strategy was to expose the culprits and deal with them
according to the law. He asked the people -- workers, civil
servants, -- to expose such people as they were enemies of
justice and the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said the second strategy was to look afresh into the
law, regulations, and the whole government and public sector
working system with a view to plugging loop holes contributing to
the growth of corrupt practices.
</P>
<P>
The president listed some of the areas where such loop holes
existed such as commercial and non-commercial agreements, civil
service regulations, licensing, tax collection, tender awards,
auditing and in the very system of service dispensation.
</P>
<P>
He said there was need also to review the Corruption
Prevention Act of 1971 and how to go about implementing the
Leadership Code Act of 1995. To this end, he asked the commission
to present to him a specific report on this within three months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Mkapa said all those who owed public
finance institutions should be cornered and made to pay according
to the existing laws. "If you borrow, you must pay, that's the
practice," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
