<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Endangered Animals Under Protection in Qinling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The endangered animals, including
giant pandas, crested ibis and golden monkeys, have been put under
effective protection in the Qinling mountains in northwest China's
Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
So far, a total of 29 giant pandas, 60 crested ibis and 26
golden monkeys have been rescued and bred in the local wildlife
nursing center.
</P>
<P>
Among the 29 rescued pandas, six have returned to the wild. The
crested ibis have increased from the original seven to the present
60 while the artificial breeding of golden monkeys has made the
number of such animals rise to 26.
</P>
<P>
Experts said this is the result of the steps taken by the
province, including implementation of relevant regulations, to
protect the endangered species living in these areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulations, hunting of the endangered animals
are banned and those who violate the rules will face severe
punishment.
</P>
<P>
To further improve the protection of the wildlife, the province
will set up two more nature reserves and four panda protection
stations in the Qinling mountains.
</P>
<P>
At present, an estimated 1,000 giant pandas are living in the
wild in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
