<HEADLINE> Uganda Not To Join SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Uganda will not join the
Southern African development Community (SADC) because it prefers
to the regional organization, the Common Market of Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA).
</P>
<P>
An official statement issued here today by the Ugandan
Ministry of Trade and Industry said that Uganda was implementing
the COMESA decisions which include reduction of tariffs by 70
percent, liberalization of foreign exchange and facilitation of
road transit.
</P>
<P>
It disclosed that last month, Zimbabwe had asked Uganda to
join the SADC but the request was still under consideration by
the government.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA, according to the statement, recently held a
special meeting of the council of ministers in Lusaka, which
considered challenges facing the sub-regional body, particularly
the critical financial situation resulting from delays and
non-payment of contributions by member states.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka meeting agreed that a joint COMESA and SADC summit
would be held soon to resolve issues relating to coordination and
harmonization of activities of the two bodies.
</P>
<P>
It adopted on June 30 this year as the deadline for honoring
all outstanding obligations by member states.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also called for speedy ratification of the treaty
establishing the COMESA by members who had not yet done so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
