<HEADLINE> More Individual Households Have Telephones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 33.84 million Chinese
households got access to a telephone during the 1991-95 period,
nine times 1990's figure, "Workers' Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
On average, there was an increase of 40,000 telephones every
day, 70 percent of which were in individual households.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 4.7 telephones for every 100 households,
3.6 percent higher than 1991's figure. The ratio is expected to
climb to 10.5 percent by the year 2000, at which time almost all
households in urban areas will have a telephone.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, the capacity of the national telephone network is
expected to reach 420 million lines, ranking first in the world,
the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
The country now has 3.62 million mobile phone users and 50,000
digital communication customers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 08:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: With Europe's "Engines" in Trouble, Single Currency Meets Red Light  (By Kang Xinwen) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- As European integration moves
ahead after EU leaders renewed their resolve at last month's
Madrid summit, gloomy economic prospects in Germany and France
signalled a red light on the road to a single currency.
</P>
<P>
Economists predict that France, the self-proclaimed political
leader of the European Union, will see growth of only 1 percent to
1.5 percent in 1996 and, therefore, may find it impossible to
qualify for the 3 percent deficit-to-GDP criterion by 1997.
</P>
<P>
And Germany, usually Europe's economic front-runner, only
witnessed 1.9 percent growth in 1995. Its deficit-to-GDP jumped
from 2.9 percent to 3.6 percent, depriving it for the first time
of its right to preach to others.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that by 1997, when EU members will begin talks on
who can join the single currency, Germany's deficit-to-GDP may
further jump to between 4.6 percent and 5.1 percent as its growth
may dip to a new low.
</P>
<P>
German Economics Minister Guenther Rexrodt recently predicted
that his country's economic growth in 1996 would be below 2
percent and more pessimistic economists have predicted the rate
will be no higher than 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development
earlier estimated that if Germany's economic growth failed to
reach 3 percent, every 0.5 percent decrease in growth will be
coupled with a 0.5 percent deficit hike.
</P>
<P>
To reverse the deficit's upward trend, France and Germany have
to either adopt budget-cutting policies or to stimulate economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
But a budget-slashing program in France to cut the deficit and
to qualify the country for the Euro sparked off crippling strikes
nationwide, the worst since the 1968 worker-student uprising.
</P>
<P>
In neighboring Germany, where the jobless make up 10 percent of
the population, any budget-slashing plan may also trigger massive
social unrest.
</P>
<P>
The other alternative, stimulating economic growth, may bring
lower deficits in the long term. But it may also fuel inflation
and a temporary deficit climb in the short term and, therefore,
cannot prepare the two countries for the criterion by 1997.
</P>
<P>
The consensus among press commentators is that without France
and Germany, Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) will make no sense
as the two "European engines" have been the initiators and
vigorous backers of European integration.
</P>
<P>
The late French President Francois Mitterrand and German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl in 1990 jointly proposed the creation of
the EMU as well as a political union.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the two countries have repeatedly suggested that a
Franco-German monetary union be created first to spur the creation
of the EMU.
</P>
<P>
The EMU, agreed upon in the Maastricht Treaty in 1991, was
originally set to be launched in 1997 when members should meet the
criteria for 3 percent deficit-to-GDP and 60 percent public
debt-to-GDP.
</P>
<P>
But EU leaders, fearing that most member countries would not
recover from their economic slump and meet the convergence
criteria, approved a blueprint to launch the Euro on January 1,
1999, at last month's Madrid summit.
</P>
<P>
In the face of widespread recession across Europe, some experts
have put forward two other approaches to a single currency -- to
put off its creation again or to lower the criteria.
</P>
<P>
But the EU Commission stressed that the launch date would
tolerate no delay, saying that otherwise the creation of a single
currency will be pushed further and further away.
</P>
<P>
The commission said that people would lose faith in the EMU,
the first step towards a united Europe, if it was delayed again
and again.
</P>
<P>
However, the commission did not say a definite no to the idea
of lowering the criteria, though it has hesitated to say yes for
fear that it might lead to limitless deficits among EU members.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the Euro, whether or not it is born
on time, will bring more troubles to the 15-nation EU before its
birth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 08:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Improve Machine Building Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Over the next 15 years, China
will exert great effort to improve its machine building industry
as a pillar of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Statistics provided by the Ministry of Machine-building
Industry show that during the 1991-1995 period, the sector's
annual growth in output value reached 21 percent, with pre-tax
profits totalling 141.7 billion yuan, up 72.2 percent over the
1986-1990 period.
</P>
<P>
The five years witnessed the use of 7.15 billion US dollars in
overseas funds, earning 86.5 billion US dollars in foreign
exchange, an annual increase of 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), more effort will
be put into improving machine products, maximizing enterprises'
efforts and ability to develop new products.
</P>
<P>
The industry is set to promote 1,000 name-brand products, and
set up 100 large-scale, profitable and competitive enterprises,
and will establish 300 technology development centers.
</P>
<P>
By the turn of the century, the auto industry will set up three
to four enterprises each with annual sales exceeding 40 billion
yuan, and the motorcycle sector will set up 10 enterprises each
with annual sales of more than five billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Five enterprises will have annual sales of 10 billion yuan
each, 20 enterprises each will have sales of five billion yuan,
and 60 enterprises each will have sales of two billion yuan, in
other machinery sectors.
</P>
<P>
The industry's total output value is expected to reach about
1.5 trillion yuan by the year 2000, and increase more than 100
percent over that year's figure by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The industry's output value will rise from one-fourth of the
country's industrial total in 1992 to one-third by 2010.
</P>
<P>
In 2000, the industry will get 34 billion US dollars in foreign
exchange, with its portion in the country's total export volume
climbing from 1992's 14.9 percent to more than 20 percent, which
will make the industry the country's No.1 foreign exchange earner.
</P>
<P>
Also in 2010, the industry will earn 130 billion US dollars in
foreign exchange, with its proportion of the country's total
exceeding 25 percent. The industry will be among the world's top
10 in export volume.
</P>
<P>
Numerically-controlled machine tools will account for 70
percent of the domestic market by 2000, and 80 percent by
2010. Priority will be given to hydraulic, pneumatic, sealed
products, and low-voltage equipment, moulds, bearings,
instruments, and meters.
</P>
<P>
During the 1996-2000 period, about 146.2 billion yuan will be
needed for automotive investment, 141.2 billion yuan of which will
be for autos and the rest for motorcycles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
