<HEADLINE> Schools Spread Marriage, Child-Bearing Knowledge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGDONG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- "I have learned a lot about
child-bearing and other matters from this school," Tuo Yuzhong
said while walking out of the school gate with his newly-wed.
</P>
<P>
The Marriage and Child-bearing School of Baitu Township in
Gaoyao City in south China's Guangdong Province is one of the
thousands of such schools in the province, according to Li
Liqiang, director of the Baitu Family Planning Office, who is also
the only full-time teacher of such a school in Baitu.
</P>
<P>
Founded by Deng Aitong, head of the township, in 1987, it was
the first of its kind in the province.
</P>
<P>
"We used to have classes in a small room where the only
equipment we had was a slide projector," Deng said.
</P>
<P>
Now it has moved into a large classroom which is equipped with
a tv set and a video cassette recorder.
</P>
<P>
Deng invites Li and six part-time teachers from a local
hospital, the women's federation and the judicial department to
give lectures on sex, eugenics and the country's family planning
policies, he said.
</P>
<P>
The school also invites local pregnant women, young mothers and
senior women to give listeners advices about motherhood and child
care and regular lectures on sex to local middle-school students.
</P>
<P>
It sponsors courses for local newly-weds once a month, he said.
</P>
<P>
They are so popular that many newly-weds from the nearby
villages ride motorcycles to attend classes, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li, in his 30's, has been in his post for more than 10
years. He used to be unwelcome among local young people, but now
he has become their friends, Li said.
</P>
<P>
"It doesn't work to rely on administrative measures and
economic sanction only," he said. "We must let the farmers
understand the advantages in having fewer children."
</P>
<P>
Due to the efforts of Deng's school, 95 percent of the couples
who have attended the classes have not violated family planning
policies, Li said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
