<HEADLINE> Family Planning Associations Help Farmers Prosper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 18 (Xinhua) -- "I don't want to have a son
as long as I can earn enough money," Chen Fangqiang, owner of a
grocery store in Gaoyao City, Guangdong Province, said.
</P>
<P>
Chen made the remark when told that he could have the second
child according to the local family planning policy which permits
rural couples at the child-bearing age to have the second child if
their first child is a girl.
</P>
<P>
More and more farmers like Chen in Gaoyao in south China's
Guangdong Province are now favoring a one-child family due to the
efforts of local family planning associations which are helping
them achieve prosperity, according to Liao Daqing, director of the
Gaoyao City Family Planning commission.
</P>
<P>
"My work will be easier if all local farmers enjoy tangible
benefits from the family planning policy," he said.
</P>
<P>
The city now has 1,020 family planning associations at all
levels, with a total of 54,800 members, all of whom are farmers,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The associations are organized by government officials in
charge of family planning. All farmers implementing the family
planning program can apply for joining the associations.
</P>
<P>
Most associations have set up businesses to help members plant
fruit trees and vegetables and raise fish, bullfrogs and chickens,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The businesses also provide to the members chemical fertilizers
and fodder at reduced prices, as well as information, consulting
and technical services.
</P>
<P>
Part of the profits made by the businesses are used to buy
old-age pension insurance policies for one-child families and
families with two daughters only, he said.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Guangsheng, 37, member of a local family planning
association who is good at raising fish, used to live on his 0.13
ha plot as he did not have enough money to own a fish pond.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the association, he contracted a 3.3-ha fish
pond with a 20,000 yuan loan (about 2,410 US dollars) from a
credit co-op in 1992.
</P>
<P>
"I repaid the loan plus interests the following year and in
1995 I earned more than 70,000 yuan," he said.
</P>
<P>
The associations have enabled farmers break away from such
traditional ideas as "more sons mean greater blessings to the
parents," Miao said.
</P>
<P>
Deng Qunsen, a father of two daughters, intended to have a
son. But his mother strongly objected to his idea, saying: "With
three mouths, how can you give a good education to your son?"
</P>
<P>
He attended an evening class sponsored by a local family
planning association to learn how to grow vegetables.
</P>
<P>
"I believe I can also get rich like others," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
