<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 07:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang's Underground Irrigation System Reopened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Karez, the
largest underground irrigation system with a history of about
3,000 years, has made a comeback in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, after years of disuse.
</P>
<P>
The crystal clear, cool water is once again flowing from
hundreds of the Karez which dried up in the 1980s in the Turfan
and Hamin basins. The Turfan Basin, 60 km from the Tianshan
Mountains, is famous for its grapes and melons.
</P>
<P>
The snow of the Tianshan Mountains produces underflow into the
karezes of the two basins, which are 1,400 meters lower than the
mountainous areas. The Turfan Basin is 154 meters below sea level,
and the sticky soil of the desert has a lot of calcium that keeps
the structure of the karez strong and difficult to cave in.
</P>
<P>
The karez, extending three to five km, consists of an
underground channel, a ditch on the surface, and a well and
cistern that give access. The well is used to clear, repair, or
ventilate the karez underground which runs between wells for a
distance of from 20 to 70 meters.
</P>
<P>
Patar, an old master of karez construction in Turfan City who
changed jobs in the 1980s, has been asked by farmers and local
officials to take up his old trade again.
</P>
<P>
With his help, hundreds of dry karezes have come back to life
after farmers in the two basins launched a campaign to dredge,
strengthen, or extend karezes in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
With a total length of 3,000 to 5,000 km, some 1,000 karezes
have been used to irrigate hundreds of thousands of hectares of
farmland in the two basins and an increasing part of the desert is
being turned into oases.
</P>
<P>
Ma Jingui, agriculture division chief of Turfan Prefecture,
says that karez water contributes a lot to the prefecture's "grape
economy".
</P>
<P>
The prefecture produced a record 270,000 tons of grapes, worth
600 million yuan, giving farmers an average of 800 yuan (nearly
100 US dollars) from grape production each year, or about half of
an average farmer's annual income, Ma noted.
</P>
<P>
"It is said that annual raisin output in Turfan accounts for
five percent of the world's total," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although modern irrigation systems are available in Xinjiang,
no irrigation system is comparable to the karez for its low cost
and cleanness. Farmers point out that it needs no power for
water-flowing since the mountain is 1,400 meters higher than the
basins. Also, little water is lost to evaporation and the volume
of water is fairly stable all year round.
</P>
<P>
Yao Jian, a local water conservation official, said the average
annual rainfall in Turfan Prefecture is only 16 mm and evaporation
is as high as 3,000 mm.
</P>
<P>
Average annual groundwater runoff totals 1.07 billion cu.m. in
the Turfan but the total volume of annual consumption of water
reaches 1.2 billion cu.m, the official said, attributing the
disparity to the repeated use of water from the karez.
</P>
<P>
The karez serves as a natural air conditioner for people in the
Turfan Basin, where it is usually hotter in the summer than in
other parts of the country. Inside the karez, it remains cool in
summer and a bit mild in winter.
</P>
<P>
The karez have attracted thousands of tourists from both China
and abroad in recent years and provides water for local residents'
daily use.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0200 </DOCNO>
