<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 07:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hangzhou's Garbage to Be Used to Generate Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian company is set to
help Hangzhou, capital city of east China's Zhejiang Province, to
turn its garbage into electric power.
</P>
<P>
With the assistance of Environmental Technologies Inc. of
Calgary, Canada, a garbage power plant, the first of its kind in
China, will be set up to make use of methane.
</P>
<P>
Plans call for six generating units with a total installed
capacity of 6,000 kw. to be built. The first unit will be
assembled in the second quarter of the year and is expected to
produce power by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Waste materials have generally been buried in Chinese cities,
but accumulation of methane can trigger an explosion if the air
contains five to 15 percent of methane.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, an explosion occured at a garbage dump in Yueyang City
of central China's Hunan Province, destroying nearby facilities
and sending more than 20,000 cubic meters of debris into the air.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, another explosion occurred in Chongqing, in
Sichuan province, because of similar conditions, that left six
people dead.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that methane can also damage crops and the ozone
layer. It can, at the same time, be a fine form of energy. One ton
of garbage can produce 220 cubic meters of methane, and one cubic
meters of methane can produce 1.5 to two kwh of power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 07:35 </DATE_TIME>
