<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serbs Agree to Join Sarajevo Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior Western envoy said in
Pale today that he had reached an agreement with the Bosnian Serbs
on the latter's participation in a commission in settling the
Sarajevo issue.
</P>
<P>
Michael Steiner, a chief European Union (EU) negotiator, struck
the deal with the Serbs today at a meeting with Bosnian Serb Prime
Minister Rajko Kasagic and Assembly Speaker Momcilo Krajisnik in
Pale outside Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
Under the Dayton peace accord, officially signed in Paris on
December 14, a joint commission consisting of Bosnian Serbs,
Muslims and Croats will be set up to settle the issue of Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
Steiner, deputy to Carl Bildt, senior EU representative for
Bosnia, said he believes that a solution will be found on the
Sarajevo issue with the participation of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
He added that he understands the Serbs' concern over their
safety under Moslem rule.
</P>
<P>
Large numbers of Serbs are ready to leave Sarajevo, saying that
they distrust the assurances of the Muslim-led government that
they will be safe.
</P>
<P>
Also today, at a meeting with Krajisnik, IFOR Commander Admiral
Leighton Smith appealed to Serbs to stay in Sarajevo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
