<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 07:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Tighten Soccer Crowd Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- More strict crowd control
moves are to be taken for future soccer matches set for the Hong
Kong Stadium, according to a soccer meeting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The moves were worked out after an on-field brawl, which
happened last Saturday here and involved players and an official
of local First Division clubs South China and Uhlsport Rangers.
</P>
<P>
Among the moves, about five extra policemen will be deployed
for matches, aimed mainly at controlling the crowds near the fence
at the end of the games. And extra police are to be brought in to
escort players from the ground.
</P>
<P>
A temporary barrier would be erected behind the teams' reserve
booths on the pitch sidelines to separate players and officials
from fans.
</P>
<P>
In addition, stewards had been told to tighten security at the
main gate by increasing bag checks for bottles and cans.
</P>
<P>
The moves were approved at a closed-door between stadium
managers Wembley International, the Hong Kong Football Association
(HKFA), the Urban Services Department and local police.
</P>
<P>
"This arrangement will be in place for the next three to four
soccer matches," said Chief Inspector Fung Tak-yin, divisional
police commander of Happy Valley where the stadium is located.
</P>
<P>
"These measures are only a short-term change and we will see
how it goes," he added.
</P>
<P>
Steward Lee Leung-nang, chairman of the HKFA, said, "I agree
that Hong Kong spectators are very well behaved, but we still have
to take precautions to ensure a similar incident doesn't happen
again."
</P>
<P>
The disciplinary committee of the HKFA is to meet Monday to
discuss the incident and some penalty decisions against offenders
are thought to be taken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
