<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 07:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Funds in China to Develop Offshore Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China has received 5.1 billion
U.S. dollars' worth of foreign investment to develop its offshore
oil and gas, accounting for 58 percent of the country's total
input in this sector.
</P>
<P>
According to the China National Offshore Oil Corporation
(CNOOC), China has signed 109 contracts and agreements with 62 oil
companies from 16 countries and regions for joint efforts to tap
China's huge offshore oil and gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
Sino-foreign cooperative exploration has verified offshore oil
reserves of 1.25 billion tons and 235 billion cu m of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Some 17 offshore oil and gas fields are operational, with an
annual crude output of 9 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Officials say that CNOOC has turned over to the State a total
of 4.13 billion yuan in taxes over the past 13 years since its
inauguration and has developed total assets worth 1.7 billion yuan
in 1983 to the present 32.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The CNOOC officials noted that the country's annual offshore
oil and gas output is expected to top 13 million tons and 3.15
billion cu m, respectively, in the coming five years.
</P>
<P>
An authoritative source revealed that major breakthroughs are
forecast for this year for utilization of offshore oil and gas,
including construction of an 8-million-ton oil refinery and a
450,000-ton ethylene project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
