<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 07:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China's Farmers Busier in Winter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- It is a world of ice and snow
with the temperature as low as 30 degrees centigrade below zero in
Northeast China Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
However, cucumber, beans, melons and other vegetables are
growing luxuriantly in the plastic sheet-covered fields in
Zhaodong City.
</P>
<P>
While packing up fresh vegetable for a nearby market, Zhang
Weiyan, a farmer of Haicheng Town, said the old days of staying at
home idly to pass the freezing cold winter season has gone.
</P>
<P>
"Most of us have built warm-up houses to plant vegetables and
melons, and we have to get up earlier to learn market information,
grow vegetable and melons, and sell them to the market," he noted
and disclosed that farmers nowadays earn more than before.
</P>
<P>
Wang Fu is a 41-year-old farmer from Shuangshan Village of
Zhaodong City.
</P>
<P>
After driving more than 600 sheep to the field to eat maize
stalks, he went to households specialized in raising cattle to
collect manure, and then ship them to his contract field to
prepare for spring farming.
</P>
<P>
The farmer with a background of senior middle school felt "a
bright prospect in growing grain" because the state has raised the
grain-purchased prices, and relieved all burdens for farmers
except the agricultural tax.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that he earned 350,000 yuan last year, and has bought
five tractors. He plans to plant 47 hectares of land this year.
</P>
<P>
Liu Mingjiu, a farmer at Songzhan Town, is specialized in
raising pigs.
</P>
<P>
Pointing at the rows of tide pigpens, Liu said happily that he
is raising 600 pigs valued at 480,000 yuan. "All of them are
growing well," he said.
</P>
<P>
Farmers living along the banks the Songhua River in Zhaodong
city have turned out to dig ice and catch fish with drill steel
and fishing tackles, and then sell them to urban districts.
</P>
<P>
According to Tian Fengshan, the provincial governor, some 20
million farmers are making use of the slack winter season to learn
scientific farming skills.
</P>
<P>
A meeting room of Jucheng Village is often squeezed with crowds
of farmers, old and young and male and female, watching
documentary films about agro-techniques.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
