<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 07:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO General Satisfied with Peace Mission in Bosnia  (By Jiang Yaping) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, January 17 (Xinhua) -- NATO peace mission has been
carried out smoothly in Bosnia and the Dayton peace accord will be
implemented, IFOR commander Leighton Smith told Xinhua today at
the IFOR headquarters in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
"I have inspected a lot of troops and I think they are
extraordinarily professional and they are exactly what I expected
to see," the U.S. Admiral said.
</P>
<P>
He added that he is "particularly impressed by the leadership"
of the IFOR troops and also satisfied with the soldiers who know
precisely what their job is.
</P>
<P>
Under the Dayton peace accord officially signed last month in
Paris, a 60,000-strong NATO-led multinational peace implementation
force (IFOR) will be deployed in Bosnia to enforce the accord.
</P>
<P>
About 35,000 troops have already arrived in the war-torn
country since they formally took over from the U.N. peace-keeping
forces on December 20.
</P>
<P>
Smith said his troops' priority at the moment is to dissuade
the Serbs from leaving Sarajevo, which under the Dayton accord
will be unified and put into the control of the Muslim-led
government as from March 19.
</P>
<P>
"What I am trying to do now is to project correct information
about what the peace process is, correct information about what
IFOR is doing and will do, so that all the people in Sarajevo will
be able to make a choice to go where they want."
</P>
<P>
The 65-year-old general complained that the Bosnian government
has not made enough efforts to calm the Serbs' fear and make them
to stay.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, thousands of Serbs have left their homes
in Sarajevo, and some even torched their houses before
leaving. According to Serb sources, the Serb-controlled areas in
Sarajevo have a population of more than 120,000.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian government has been working on an amnesty law which
will be distributed particularly to the Sarajevo Serbs who plan to
leave for fear of possible retaliation, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
But he emphasized that IFOR troops are only responsible for the
military aspects of the peace accord, not the civilian ones. "It
is not my job to be the final arbiter in all potential peace
non-compliance issues."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the failed exchange of POWs on January 15
and 16, which was scrapped by the Bosnian government on the ground
that the Serbs refused to release 4,000 detained civilians and war
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
If the conflicting sides fail to exchange all the POWs by
January 19, it will be a first heavy blow to the implementation of
the Dayton accord.
</P>
<P>
The IFOR commander said he strongly favors an integrated police
force comprising both Muslims and Serbs to patrol the Serb
Sarajevo areas after the Serb troops' withdrawal on January 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 07:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ CPI Index Continues to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Consumers Price Index
rose by 0.6 percent in New Zealand during the December 1995
quarter, bringing the 1995 calendar year's figure to 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics New Zealand said today the 0.6 percent increase
compares with increases of 0.2 percent and 1.0 percent in the
September and June quarters.
</P>
<P>
Economists blamed the booming housing market in the country's
largest city Auckland for pushing the index higher. The average
house price in the city has climbed one third in the past two
years to 200,000 dollars (130,000 U.S. dollars), 50,000 dollars
higher than the national figure.
</P>
<P>
But apart from housing which increased by 1.2 percent in the
quarter, Statistics New Zealand figures also showed a 0.9 percent
rise in grocery food prices, including those for milk, bread and
bread rolls, aerated soft drinks and potato crisps and snack food.
</P>
<P>
In the quarter, prices also went up for newspapers, writing
paper and refills, women's clothing, furniture, used cars and
vehicle insurance, as well as long-distance bus, rail and ferry
fares and domestic airfares.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
