<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 07:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Open Courses for 800,000 Principals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The State Education Commission
has decided to educate 800,000 headmasters of middle and primary
schools, or 80 percent of the total number of principals, over the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
According to a plan released here today, the principals will be
asked to learn modern educational concepts and improve their
management skills.
</P>
<P>
Each of them will have to spend at least 200 hours at a special
training center or teacher training school before he or she is
accredited.
</P>
<P>
The commission's statistics show that more than 35 percent of
the middle school teachers have not yet acquired academic
credentials as prescribed by law, and the proportion in primary
schools is 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
A headmaster of a Chinese school was in most cases in the past
a former teacher at the school.
</P>
<P>
The commission urged provincial governments to draw up detailed
plans for a training program. There is already a national teacher
training center as well as more than 2,000 teacher training
schools in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
