<HEADLINE> Shanghai Futures Trading up 71 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Turnover on the Shanghai
Commodities Exchange, Shanghai Metal Exchange, and Shanghai Cereal
and Oil Exchange, the city's three futures markets, soared 71
percent to 2.57 trillion yuan (about 310 billion US dollars) in
1995, according to the latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
The commodity exchange for the first time became the largest
futures exchange in this economic center by recording a turnover
of 1.94 trillion yuan, about 75 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The three exchanges have pledged to follow the principle of
"existence through standardization and development through
stabilization" mapped out by the China Securities Regulatory
Commission (CSRC), the country's securities watchdog.
</P>
<P>
Li Jingmou, chairman of the Zhengzhou Commodities Exchange,
China's first futures exchange founded in 1990 in central China's
Henan Province, said the strict measures the CSRC has taken to
regulate the country's fledging futures market since last year
will in the long run prove beneficial to the healthy development
of the industry.
</P>
<P>
China currently has 15 futures exchanges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
