<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 06:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Lower Investment in Telecom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China plans to use 90 billion
yuan of fixed assets investment in postal and telecommunications
project this year, which is almost the same volume as that in
1995, today's "China Daily" quoted Wu Jichuan, minister of the
postal and telecommunications industry as saying.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts attribute this a lot to the government's
tight money policy and strict control over foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
The sector is expected to get a total of 125.6 billion yuan in
revenue this year, up 28 percent over 1995, and to have a total of
130 billion yuan in traffic volume, an increase of 34 percent over
1995, according to Wu Jichuan.
</P>
<P>
Wu also announced the sector's strategic development targets
for the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000):
</P>
<P>
The sector's traffic volume will grow at an annual average rate
of 25 percent, while the revenues will rise at a rate of 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
A total of 500 billion yuan will be invested in the sectors'
fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
The country's long-distance telephone switching capacity will
be added 2.5 million lines, bringing the total up to 6 million
lines.
</P>
<P>
The country's public phone switching capacity will also rise
from the present 91 million lines to 170 million lines by the year
of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The subscribers of telephones, including that of mobile phones,
will climb from the current 44.3 million to 123 million.
</P>
<P>
As a result, there will be 30 to 40 telephones for every 100
people in the country's urban areas, and an average of 10.5
telephones for every 100 people in the countryside by the turn of
this century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
