<HEADLINE> Indian Court Asks CBI to Submit Papers on Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Indian special judge V.B.
Gupta Wednesday asked the Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) to
submit documents and other relevant papers in support of the
charges filed Tuesday in the 65-crore rupee Hawala racket, the
Times of India reported today.
</P>
<P>
The court directed the CBI to submit these documents by January
29.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, the CBI Tuesday filed charges
against seven leading politicians, including Bharatiya Janata
party (BJP) President L.K. Advani, and sought the president's
sanction to prosecute three cabinet ministers for their
involvement in the Hawala scandal.
</P>
<P>
The move has led to the resignation of all the three ministers
-- Agriculture Minister Balram Jakhar, Human Resources Development
Minister Madhavrao Scindia, and Water Resources and Parliamentary
Affairs Minister Vidya Charan Shukla -- Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
In a related report today, the Times of India said it has got
photocopies of six charge sheets filed against the seven
politicians.
</P>
<P>
The papers showed that the politicians had received huge bribes
from the suspected Hawala dealers (persons involved in illegal
trading of foreign exchange). The bribes had been paid under
three categories -- departmental expenses, political expenses and
other expenses.
</P>
<P>
According to the papers, the Hawala dealers had paid six
million rupees (about 168,000 US dollars) to BJP leader Advani, 10
million rupees (about 279,000 dollars) to former deputy prime
minister Devi Lal, and 1.05 million rupees (about 29,000 dollars)
to All India Indira Congress (breakaway faction of the ruling
Congress Party) Working President Arjun Singh.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
