<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conspirators of Bomb Plot Get Stiff Sentences in N.Y. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A blind Egyptian cleric and
nine followers convicted of plotting a "war of urban terrorism"
in New York were sentenced here today to long prison terms despite
their professions of innocence.
</P>
<P>
They were convicted of plotting to blow up the United Nations,
the headquarters of the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) in
Manhattan, the Lincoln and Holland tunnels and the George
Washington Bridge in New York in a single day of terror.
</P>
<P>
Under high intense security, the Manhattan federal court
sentenced Sheik Omar Abdel-Rahman, 57-year old Muslim cleric and
the spiritual leader of the conspiracy, to life imprisonment
without parole for plotting to kill Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
One of his followers, El Sayyid Nosair, was also sentenced to
life in prison for his role in the bomb plot and for killing the
anti-Arab militant Rabbi Meir Kahane in a New York hotel in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The other eight defendants received prison terms of 25 to 57
years for what the prosecutors called a "war of urban terrorism"
aimed at altering U.S. policy in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Their convictions represented the biggest terrorism trial in
the U.S. history and were related to the bombing of the World
Trade Center in New York on February 26, 1993, which killed six
people and injured more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
During the trial, a large group of police officers wearing
bulletproof vests and armed with semiautomatic weapons guarded the
federal courthouse and two bomb-sniffing dogs patrolled with
federal agents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
