<HEADLINE> Greece Sets Up Liaison Office in Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Greece today formally opened its
liaison office in the Macedonian capital of Skoplje, a move hailed
as a major step in improving ties between the two former foes.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of liaison offices by Greece and Macedonia
in each other's capitals is an important event," reports reaching
here quoted Aleksander Malas, first director of the Greek office,
as telling a ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The event will increase the momentum that has been gained by
the signing in New York in September of a temporary agreement on
the normalization of their relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Macedonian Foreign Ministry described the
establishment as the first step in implementing the agreement.
</P>
<P>
After the signing of the agreement, Greece lifted its trade
sanctions on Macedonia which was imposed in 1993 after the latter
refused to change its name and national flag. On its part, the
former Yugoslav republic revised the design on its national flag.
</P>
<P>
The two countries failed to reach agreement on the name of
Macedonia, which Greece says implies Macedonia's territorial
claims for one of its provinces of the same name, at the latest
talks last week. But the two sides agreed to continue their
negotiations. 
</P>
