<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Provide Credits to Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
announced the approval of credits totaling some 151 million U.S.
dollars for health projects in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
A credit of 101 million dollars will go to the National Health
Support Project which aims to expand access to primary health
care to 40 million people in 30 of Vietnam's 36 provinces.
</P>
<P>
About 50 million dollars will go toward the Population and
Family Health Project, which aims to reduce Vietnam's population
growth to 1.7 percent, downsize its population to no more than 82
million, and achieve a national infant mortality rate of 30 per
thousand and maternal mortality rate of 70 per thousand.
</P>
<P>
It will benefit more than half of the total population of
Vietnam by 2003, the World Bank said.
</P>
<P>
The credits are extended on the standard favorable terms of the
International Development Association, a World Bank affiliate.
</P>
