<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Criticizes Honduran Navy Chief's Statements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguan Foreign Minister
Ernesto Leal described Honduran navy chief's statements on
Honduras' readiness to use force in a maritime dispute between the
two countries as "deplorable" and "out-of-place."
</P>
<P>
"I have read the statements supposedly made by Bruno Fontana,
the commander of Honduras' navy, and frankly they are deplorable
and truly out of place," said Leal who was quoted today by the
newspaper La Tribuna.
</P>
<P>
In his statements, Fontana said that the Honduran navy does not
rule out the use of force in a maritime dispute in the Pacific
Ocean between the two countries, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper today quoted the Nicaraguan foreign minister as
saying that his country may lodge a protest over Fontana's
statements and "we are in contact with the Honduran foreign
minister to talk about this matter."
</P>
<P>
Leal and his Honduran counterpart Ernesto Paz Aguilar will meet
today to discuss the maritime boundary dispute which has sparked
several incidents between Nicaraguan naval forces and Honduran
fishermen in the Caribbean Sea and the Gulf of Fonseca.
</P>
<P>
In the latest incident, Nicaraguan navy captured three Honduran
fishing boats and 90 crewmen. One Honduran crew member was wounded
in an exchange of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
Leal said the two sides will try to establish a "zone of
tolerance" between the two countries "while we establish the
limits of the Caribbean Sea."
</P>
<P>
The meeting between the two foreign ministers was agreed upon
during a meeting between Nicaraguan President Violeta Chamorro and
Honduran President Carlos Roberto Reina in Guatemala City when
they attended the inaugural ceremony of Guatemala's new President
Alavaro Arzu Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
