<HEADLINE> EU Warns UEFA to Accept Court's Rule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission warned
UEFA on Wednesday to accept the decision of European Court of
Justice on the football transfer system or tough sanctions will be
taken.
</P>
<P>
The Commision would write to UEFA in the days ahead telling it
the judgment had to be obeyed, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
UEFA and FIFA reaffirmed their opposition to the EU judgment,
but expressed their willing to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
Last month the court abolished the existing limits on
three-foreigners in a team, allowing as many foreign players in
European Union clubs as wanted. Transfer fees for out-of-contract
players were also scrapped, due to the Bosman issue.
</P>
<P>
Both FIFA and UEFA responded in a joint statement Wednesday,
confirming their stance to maintain the existing restrictions.
</P>
<P>
But the Commission insisted that "reasonable propositions"
should be forwarded by UEFA in conformity with EU labour laws, or
it would take supplementary measures, including fines.
</P>
<P>
If necessary, the Commision may skip UEFA to contact directly
with European leagues, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
