<HEADLINE> Poland Offers Military Bases to IFOR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Polish President Aleksander
Kwasniewski said today that NATO's implementation force (IFOR)
enforcing the Bosnian peace treaty could use Polish military
facilities if necessary.
</P>
<P>
He made the offer during his meeting with NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana and members of the Council of
Permanent Representatives at NATO headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Solana said he appreciated the offer and would consider it,
adding that NATO laid great stress on deepening cooperation with
Poland, "one of the most active partners of NATO."
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski noted that Polish soldiers, who will soon start
their peace-keeping mission in Bosnia-Herzegovina, were
fulfilling Poland's obligations as a NATO partner and promoting
peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Under the Bosnian peace agreement signed in Paris on December
14, Polish soldiers will join the 60,000-strong NATO-led
multinational peacekeeping force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
During talks with Solana, the Polish president repeated the
"strong wish" of his country to become a NATO member at an early
date. He urged NATO to map out its Eastern Expansion timetable
soon and to open talks with Poland before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
"It is both in keeping with the interests of Poland and the
demands of a new security mechanism in Europe," he said, adding
that its entry would not affect the security of Russia and other
countries.
</P>
<P>
"Poland would be loathe to see a new dividing line appear in
Europe," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
