<HEADLINE> Hangzhou Residents Support Charity (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, January 18 (Xinhua) -- "We are grateful to the
Hangzhou City Charitable Society and the numerous uncles, aunts,
brothers and sisters who have cared for us." With tears in their
eyes, two little deaf-mute girls used sign language to express
their heartfelt thanks to those who helped them return to
school.
</P>
<P>
Li Beizhi and Zheng Suliang, both ten years old, made the sign
at the end of 1995 at a meeting to mark the establishment of the
Hangzhou City Charitable Society in Hangzhou, the capital of east
China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
They dropped out of the Hangzhou School for Deaf-Mutes in 1994
because of financial difficulties. Last March the Hangzhou City
Charitable Society fetched them from their rural homes 100 km
from Hangzhou and paid their tuitions, enabling them to continue
their studies.
</P>
<P>
Li and Zheng, both fourth grade students now, are among the
best students in their class.
</P>
<P>
Li said in sign language, "I have three homes now. One is the
true one where my parents live, another is my school and still
another is the charitable society."
</P>
<P>
In recent years the charity undertaking has enjoyed support
from all sectors of society in Hangzhou, a beautiful city which is
best known for the picturesque West Lake.
</P>
<P>
An editorial in a local newspaper said, "More and more Hangzhou
residents are practicing charity, one of the traditional Chinese
virtues, in their everyday life."
</P>
<P>
Charitable campaigns, such as the campaign to help orphans and
disabled children to recover and the orphan adoption campaign
launched in 1994, are still under way.
</P>
<P>
To date, nearly 3,000 families and 30 enterprises have donated
a total of one million yuan to the Hangzhou Children's Welfare
Institute, according to Mao Tianyu, secretary general of the
Hangzhou City Charitable Society.
</P>
<P>
The money has been used to provide medical help to dozens of
orphans and disabled children in the institute suffering from
congenital heart diseases, cleft palate or other defects, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ding Hao, an orphan suffering from infantile paralysis, was
enrolled into Hangzhou University last year, with financial
assistance from a local enterprise.
</P>
<P>
He is China's first university student to come from a
children's welfare institute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Neither Expansionist Nor Aggressive, Keating Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
Paul Keating said here today that China is neither an expansionist
nor aggressive power and will not become one in the future.
</P>
<P>
"I do not believe China is an expansionist or aggressive power,
or that it is likely to become so," Keating said at the Singapore
Lecture on the theme of "Australia, Asia and the New Regionalism."
</P>
<P>
Noting that China is an essential and central part of the
regional community, he said the sheer size of its population and
economy raised questions for the rest of the world about how China
should be dealt with.
</P>
<P>
He said the economic reforms introduced by Deng Xiaoping and
President Jiang Zemin had brought profound benefits for the
international community as a whole, not just for China. Therefore,
Keating said, there was little doubt about what the broad approach
should be.
</P>
<P>
"Above all, the answer is to ensure that China is engaged
comprehensively in global and regional institutions. This has been
a major aim of APEC (Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation) and the
ASEAN (Association of South-East Asian Nations) Regional Forum to
engage China, not to contain it or attempt to isolate it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Keating, who arrived here from Malaysia this morning on a
one-day visit, met his Singapore counterpart Goh Chok Tong soon
after his arrival and left for home this evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
