<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Mayor Convicted in Finland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Court of Appeal of Turku,
about 100 kilometers southwest of Helsinki, convicted a former
mayor and two other persons of corruption today.
</P>
<P>
Former Mayor of Turku Juhani Leppa and Director of the Turku
Tax Bureau Erkki Jaaskelainen were both sentenced to serving a
nine-month term outside prison. Businessman Heikki Elia was
sentenced to one year in jail.
</P>
<P>
The three convicts sold, in January 1993, to the Finnish
Central Savings Bank the building of a real estate company, which
they jointly owned and which was to go bankrupt. They illegally
took five million markkas (about 1.02 million U.S. dollars)
from the sale as commissions.
</P>
<P>
Elia and Leppa each pocketed 1.2 million markkas (246,761
dollars) and Jaaskelainen took 800,000 markkas (164,508 dollars),
thus transferring the assets of the real estate company to
personal accounts in an effort to avoid paying debts and
inflicting huge losses on creditors.
</P>
<P>
Leppa was removed from his post last May when the Turku
District Court first handed down its ruling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
