<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Imports Up in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Australia's merchandise
imports continued to rise in December after a strong surge in the
previous month, the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS)
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The monthly merchandise imports increased by five percent to
6.59 billion Australian dollars (4.88 billion US dollars) in
December on a seasonally adjusted basis, said the ABS.
</P>
<P>
Today's figures indicated that growing domestic demand
continued to suck in imports at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Merchandise imports rose by four percent to 6.302 billion
Australian dollars (4.663 billion US dollars) last November over
the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Growing imports in the past few months indicated that
Australia's economy is regaining strength faster than expected.
This will inevitably blow up the country's trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Treasury last December revised the forecast of
current account deficit for the fiscal year of 1995-96 from 27
billion Australian dollars (20 billion US dollars) to 21 billion
Australian dollars (15.5 billion US dollars). But the latest
figures indicate that the trade deficit for 1995-1996 could be
higher than forecast.
</P>
<P>
The accelerating economic growth, combined with a strong trend
of wage growth and the impact of a prolonged budget crisis in the
United States, is expected to force the Reserve Bank of Australia
to raise interest rates before the next federal election, which is
due by May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
