<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chamber Pots Becoming A Thing of the Past in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shanghai, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Every morning, before the sun
came up, wives or husbands living in the older parts of downtown
Shanghai would step outside carrying the family's chamber pot to a
cart parked in the lane.
</P>
<P>
For generations, most residents of China's largest city lived
without the luxury of flush toilets in their houses or apartments,
but had to keep a smelly wooden pot in their livingroom or
bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past decade, at least 250,000 families have bid
farewell to the embarassing chamber pots," Shanghai's Jiefang
Daily reported earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
"There are about 300,000 families living in the Huangpu
district, and almost every family used to have a chamber pot," the
report explained, noting that, "after about 10 years of renovation
and reconstruction, only 50,000 families in the district are still
using chamber pots."
</P>
<P>
Most of the families who don't have flush toilets live in
rundown houses built around the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
In a "wipe out chamber pots campaign," the municipal government
in recent years has sped up efforts at rebuilding old houses or
levelling old ones and building new ones, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the residents of Nanshi District in the old part of
Shanghai still live in ramshackle houses and use chamber pots. But
over the last two years, the local government has rebuilt 900,000
square meters of housing and 50,000 families now enjoy the comfort
and convenience of flush toilets, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"By the year 2000, when the reconstruction project of
Shanghai's old town is complete, the last chamber pot will
hopefully be sent to be an exhibit in a history museum," the
newspaper concluded. enditem.

18/01/96 02:16 GMT
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
