<HEADLINE> Brazil Announces Targets for 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian government's
most important goals in 1996 are to generate investments, spur
economic growth and ensure fair income-distribution, President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Other goals include the recovery of bank interest rates and the
consolidation of the Real Plan, he told a press conference in the
Planalto Palace.
</P>
<P>
Brazil changed its currency from the cruzeiro to the real in
July 1994 in a bid to bring down the inflation, and the efforts
paid off in cutting the rate of inflation to 6.9 percent in July
1994 from 46 percent a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
Resolving social problems would also be a government priority
this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the work accomplished by his government in 1995,
the president highlighted efforts in the areas of health and
education.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso said that 42,000 families had been resettled last year
through the agrarian reform program, which had benefited the
country as a whole, not only landless peasants.
</P>
<P>
He denied any plans for a cabinet reshuffle and stressed the
unity of the political alliance formed during the 1994
presidential election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
