<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-18 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bright Future for China's Ship Repairers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The world's fourth largest
shipbuilder, China hopes to take advantage of its existing
infrastructure and know-how to advance its ship repair sector,
today's China Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
The report says China State Shipbuilding Corp. (CSSC), the
country's leading ship repairer, earned 1.5 billion yuan last
year, dwarfing its 1.2 billion yuan earnings of 1994.
</P>
<P>
It quotes Li Junfeng, an official with the CSSC as saying that
the volume included 85 million US dollars reaped through repairing
foreign vessels. Of those deals, nearly 60 percent of ship owners
came from abroad.
</P>
<P>
"Greece has replaced Hong Kong by taking the lion's share of
last year's orders, with more than 100 vessels to be repaired."
said Li.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the rising momentum to the completion of two big
repair docks, which have now been open for nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
One is the Chengxi floating dock in east China's Jiangsu
Province, able to handle payloads up to 100,000 DWTs (dead weight
tonnage). The other is Wenchong dry dock in Guangzhou, bearing
payloads up to 100,000 DWTs.
</P>
<P>
In addition to these, construction is underway for two more
repair docks, including a 80,000-DWT floating dock at the
mainland's southernmost port city of Beihai, and a 150,000-DWT dry
dock at Shanhaiguan along the Bohai Sea in north China.
</P>
<P>
"This year, our company has aimed for a new high, to earn 1.8
billion yuan from repairing business," Li said.
</P>
<P>
The backbone of the national repair dock layout also includes
an additional Nantong dock operating under the Ministry of
Communications, and some shipbuilders such as Jiangnan and Hudong
of Shanghai, Dalian in Liaoning and Xingang in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Now CSSC's total capacity for repairing has been lifted to more
than 500,000 DWTs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
