<HEADLINE> New Leads Discovered About Fugitive Cali Drug Lord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Police discovered
new clues that could lead to the recapture of Jose Santacruz
Londono, the third highest-ranking drug lord of the Cali Cartel,
who escaped from prison here six days ago.
</P>
<P>
Three telephone calls to Santacruz intercepted by the police
indicated that the drug lord is holed up at a ranch in a rural
area where the weather is hot and that he is in poor health, eager
for treatment for his arm.
</P>
<P>
According to a police intelligence report, Santacruz sent a
letter on Tuesday to the media in the capital, saying that during
the six months in the La Picota prison he was questioned neither
about drug trafficking nor over the death of Antioquia Governor
Antonio Roldan Betancur.
</P>
<P>
The letter, faxed from a factory in northern Cali, was
delivered by a man and a woman, young in appearance. Police are
making effort to identify and locate the two persons.
</P>
<P>
The drug lord said in the letter that he was only interrogated
on January 11 about illegal enrichment. "They asked me about two
armored vehicles owned by two very well-known people in the
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, he accused the prosecutor's office and the
"faceless" justice system of violating the law for not granting
him requisites for his health and pointed out that "I couldn't let
myself die because of that."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police sources said that in spite of the fact that
the letter has the signature and fingerprints that would supposedly
identify Santacruz, the letter has not been established as
authentic.
</P>
<P>
The government is offering a 2 billion-peso reward (about 2
million U.S. dollars) for the recapture of the drug trafficking
boss. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
