<HEADLINE> Costa Rican, U.S. to Start Talks on Lingerie Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Costa Rican government
will take a firm stand against U.S. restriction on lingerie export
in their talks scheduled to begin in Geneva Thursday, said Deputy
Foreign Trade Minister Francisco Chacon.
</P>
<P>
The United States wants to restrict exports if Costa Rican
manufacturers do not use U.S. fabrics to produce lingerie
items.
</P>
<P>
But the Central American country is unwilling to accept the
restriction. Jose Rossi, Costa Rica's foreign trade minister is
currently in Washington to seek a solution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica requested a round of consultations within the
framework of World Trade Organization (WTO) following the failure
to resolve the controversy with U.S. trade authorities.
</P>
<P>
The government of Costa Rica holds there exists no such proof
as required by WTO dispositions that the country's sales are
affecting U.S. manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, textiles producers in Costa Rica have showed their
intention to accept the U.S. proposals.
</P>
<P>
Jaime Guardia, president of the textile and apparel industry
chamber, said they prefer to accept a quota of 40 million dozens
of articles made with U.S. fabrics than keep a quota of 14.4
million that only indicates an increase of 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The industry is capable of producing 24 million dozens of items
of lingerie for women, according to the chamber. 
</P>
</TEXT>
