<HEADLINE> Vegetable Preservatives Used for Animal Semen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Preservatives used for keeping
vegetables have been used successfully for keeping oxen and sheep
semen in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region and a
breakthrough has been made in impregnating female animals using
the sperm preserved in this method.
</P>
<P>
Research on preserving livestock semen by using the vegetable
preservative was a major project for the region during the Eighth
Five-Year Plan (1990-1995), the first instance of such use both in
China and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The preservative comes from 87 chemicals extracted from 18
different plants, and has many advantages over other kinds of
preservatives. Frozen sperm protected with this method can survive
for 50 hours at 38 degrees Celsius after being thawed out.
</P>
<P>
The sperm kept in this way are effective on 78.5 percent of
cows and 68.3 percent of sheep.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that there is still much room for research in this
field because there are thousands of cold-resistant plants that
exist in nature but only 18 kinds have been used in making the
preservative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0277 </DOCNO>
