<HEADLINE> Divorce School for Saving Endangered Marriages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- "How do you save an
endangered marriage?" or "How can the rights of women and children
in divorce cases be protected?" and "What are the negative effects
of divorce on children?"
</P>
<P>
These are the kinds of questions that are now being answered in
courses offered at a special "pre-divorce school" at Renqiu City
in the central part of north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 couples applying for divorce have come here since
the school opened in July, before deciding to take the matter to
court, to learn how to properly handle such matters as division of
property and custody of children.
</P>
<P>
In the process, some couples have dropped their lawsuits and
even kept their marriages from falling apart, while those who
divorced have learned to handle matters in accordance with the
law, say school administrators who come from the city's courts of
justice and the city's Federation of Women.
</P>
<P>
The number of disputes that are the result of divorces have
also dropped after "students" learned more about the marriage law.
</P>
<P>
With a divorce rate rising from 1990's 5.9 per thousand to 7.1
per thousand last year, the number of property and custody
disputes in China has increased, and the number of criminal cases
involving the children of single-parent families' has been also on
the rise.
</P>
<P>
Similar divorce schools have been established in Beijing and
northeast China's Heilongjiang Province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
