<HEADLINE> Rich Xinjiang Farmers Help Others </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Some farmers in Shawan County in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region who have become
affluent are making efforts to help other villagers prosper.
</P>
<P>
These farmers earn an average annual income of over 100,000
yuan (about 12,044 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
At lectures organized by the local government, these skillful
farmers have been willing to share their experience with others.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zuoyi, who earned some 9,000 yuan by planting a small plot
of cucumbers last year, advised people to choose proper seeds and
not to water the plants until the first fruit on the main stem is
picked.
</P>
<P>
"I don't have to worry because there's a huge market for fresh
vegetables," he said when asked why he revealed his secrets to
others who earned only about 2,000 yuan from the same acreage.
</P>
<P>
Feng Dingwang, a villager in Sandaogoucun, who is in his early
50s, reaped an average of 7,500 kg of wheat per ha last year, much
higher than the region's average figure of 4,500 kg. At a lecture
he also introduced his experience in growing wheat.
</P>
<P>
"Such lectures are well-received by local farmers as they are
much easier to understand," said Wang Delin, deputy director of
the county, which has plans to invite agronomists to share their
farming expertise with local villagers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
