<HEADLINE> New UN Force in Croatia to Cost $128.5 Million  in Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 17 (Xinhua) - The newly established
peacekeeping operation in Croatia will cost an estimated 128.5
million dollars for the first six months, according to a report of
the U.N. chief.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the Security Council, Secretary-General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali has said that the six-month cost estimate will cover
spendings on 5,000 troops, 600 civilian police, 469 international
civilian staff and 681 locally recruited staff.
</P>
<P>
The operation, called the U.N. Transitional Administration for
Eastern Slavonia, Baranja and Western Sirmium (UNTAES), is to
oversee the return of the last Serb-held area of Croatia to
Zagreb. The lastest peace-keeping program was authorized by a
unanimous Security Council vote on Monday.
</P>
<P>
UNTAES will govern the region for an initial 12 months, with an
option of additional 12 months, under an agreement signed last
November by Croatia and the local Serbian community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
