<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average plunged 21.32 to 5,066.90 today.
</P>
<P>
The New York Stock Exchange ended a volatile session,
responding to the release of sluggish economic data.
</P>
<P>
All technology stocks took a nosedive today. The market has
some concern about the personal-computer stocks and recession
fears began to impact some of the stocks, according to some market
analysts.
</P>
<P>
The country's leading indicator of future economic activity,
which was released earlier today, fell 0.3 percent in November.
Economists had expected the leading gauge to remain stable or rise
slightly.
</P>
<P>
In a quarterly report, the Federal Reserve (Fed) said the
economy grew modestly at the end of 1995, as Christmas sales were
weak and the pace of manufacturing industry declined.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the Fed report may influence the central bank to
cut interest rates for a third time, possibly at their next
meeting beginning January 30.
</P>
<P>
In a third report, the Commerce Department reported that
America's trade deficit narrowed by 2.5 percent in October, as
both imports and exports declined.
</P>
<P>
Bonds kept their gains despite an afternoon announcement from
Washington that a budget meeting between President Clinton and top
Republicans had been canceled.
</P>
<P>
But technology stocks were hit hard after a disappointing
earnings report from Intel.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks rose with bonds and in reaction to continued
positive earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
Transportation stocks were mixed as airline stocks rose but
trucking and rail stocks declined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
