<HEADLINE> Carter to Lead Delegation to Observe Palestinian  Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. President Jimmy
Carter will lead a 40-member delegation to observe the Palestinian
general election to be held in the West Bank and Gaza on Saturday,
organizers said today.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, which comprises elected officials, academics
and international democracy advocates, will arrive in Israel
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Atlanta-based Carter Center and the National Democratic
Institute for International Affairs (NDI) are sponsoring the
mission.
</P>
<P>
"The purposes of the mission are to demonstrate international
support for democracy in the West Bank and Gaza Strip," Carter
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
And the purposes are also to "promote public confidence in the
electoral process, and to access the electoral process in relation
to Palestinian law and international norms," Carter added.
</P>
<P>
There are dozens of other U.S. and international observer
groups that will assist Palestinians during the election and
monitor it for inconsistencies.
</P>
<P>
During the last three months, representatives from the Carter
Center and NDI have been monitoring preparations for the election,
including voter and candidate registration, media coverage, and
the role of security forces.
</P>
<P>
The NDI said in a recent report that the preparations had been
"conducted in an open and conducive environment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
