<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-17 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hawaii Observatory Fire Kills Three Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A fire raged through the
world's largest and most expensive observatory on a Hawaiian
mountain top Tuesday, killed three construction workers trapped in
its dome, according to reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The fire, apparently started by a cutting torch, also injured
23 others at the Subaru Telescope Project, a 400-million-dollar
observatory under construction on top of Mauna Kea, Hawaii's
highest mountain.
</P>
<P>
The three workers trapped in the upper level of the dome were
succumbed to toxic fumes generated by burning insulation, fire
officials said. Another worker stranded on top the dome was
rescued by a county helicopter fighting a brush fire nearby.
</P>
<P>
Twenty of those injured were treated at and released from a
local hospital. But three remained hospitalized today for smoke
inhalation. They were listed in fair condition.
</P>
<P>
The observatory is expected to house a 315-inch telescope,
known as the Japan National Large Telescope and billed as the
largest and most expensive single-mirror telescope in the world.
</P>
<P>
Construction at the observatory, Japan's first major science
facility built outside the country, began in 1992 and was expected
to be completed in March.
</P>
<P>
The extent of the damage caused by the fire and its effect on
the timetable for completion were not immediately known. Twelve
other observatories are atop the 13,796-foot mountain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
