<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Perry Justified Russia's Military Attack on Chechen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Perry today justified Russia's use of military forces in
response to hostage-taking by Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
"We reject the right of any group to take hostage as a means of
implementing their policies, so therefore we believe the Russian
government is entirely correct in resisting this hostage-taking
effort and resisting it very strongly," Perry told reporters at a
picture-taking session at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
After two days of bombarding Pervomayskaya with artillery and
helicopter-fired rockets, the Russian troops today reportedly
fired salvo after salvo from powerful rocket-launchers on a
village in southern Russia near the border of breakaway Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
But Perry said that the U.S. military would not have launched
an artillery assault in the event.
</P>
<P>
"We would have, to be sure, had we been asked to conduct such
an operation...chosen a surgical operation rather than the
massive, frontal use of force," the Pentagon chief said.
</P>
<P>
"But I don't want to put myself in the position of
second-guessing the Russian military. It's a very difficult
situation there, and I wish them well," Perry added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
