<HEADLINE> Major Offered Eurosceptic Message </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister
John Major has been sent a message that his Tory government
would be continuously pressed to move in a sceptical
direction on Europe, reported Financial Times newspaper
today.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary result of the Conservative party's ever
biggest consultation process launched by Major himself in
the middle of last year showed that party members generally
were increasing disenchanted with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
In the process, about 800 meetings were held by local
Tory parties, many of which were attended by government
ministers and senior Tory party officials.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary results showed that the vast majority
indicated that they were unhappy with the interference from
Brussels in Britain's domestic affairs.
</P>
<P>
And a small minority even called for the U.K. to withdraw
from the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
The findings will make it difficult for the embattled
prime minister to respond to the concerns of pro-European
party members.
</P>
<P>
However, Major is comforted by widespread support for his
decision to keep options open on whether sterling should
join a single European currency in 1999, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
