<HEADLINE> Defendants Get Prison Terms for Bomb Plot in NY </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Three of the defendants who
were convicted of plotting a "war of urban terrorism" in the
United States were sentenced here today to 25 to 35 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
Victor Alvarez, 29, and Mohammed Saleh, 39, each received a
prison term of 35 years and Fadil Abdelghani, 33, was sentenced to
25 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
The Puerto Rican-born Alvarez was convicted of helping make
bombs and providing the plotters with weapons. The other two
defendants were convicted of a crime called seditious conspiracy.
They were found guilty of trying to use force to oppose the
authority of the United States.
</P>
<P>
All the three men said during the hearing that they were
innocent victims.
</P>
<P>
Also sentenced today will be seven other defendants including
Sheikh Omar Abdel-Rahman, the spiritual leader of the group which
were charged with planning the bombing of the United Nations, FBI
offices, bridges and tunnels in New York.
</P>
<P>
Their convictions represented the biggest terrorism trial in
U.S. history and were related to the bombing of the World Trade
Center on February 26, 1993, which killed six people and injured
more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
The sentencings, which took place under intense security at
Manhattan federal court, will last for the whole day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
