<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Urges "Adequate Response" to Chechen  Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The newly elected State Duma,
the Lower House of the Russian Parliament, today urged the
government to think of "an adequate response" to the increasing
Chechen terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In a statement circulated here tonight, the lower chamber said,
"The last actions by (Chechen separatist leader Dzhokhar) Dudayev
and his hirelings in the North Caucasus where they used the
extreme forms of terrorism necessitate an adequate response to and
measures to stop these crimes."
</P>
<P>
The statement, adopted after a discussion of the situation in
the Daghestani village of Pervomaiskoye and the Chechen conflict
in general, calls on the government "to prevent unjustified
actions which may put at risk or lead to the death of innocent
people."
</P>
<P>
The statement, adopted by a 301-24 vote with eight abstentions,
said that the Lower House "has taken the tragedy in the North
Caucasus with deep concern." The events in the Daghestani city of
Kizlyar and in Pervomaiskoye and the terrorist act against the
passengers of the Russian ferry "Avrasya" in Turkey "have shaken
Russia and the international community," it noted.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers condemned the manifestations of political and
armed terrorism and called on the Russian people to show wisdom
and restraint.
</P>
<P>
They also stressed the need to "study, in the near future, the
entire set of issues associated with the struggle against
terrorism and measures to ensure the safety of people and Russia's
territory." 
</P>
</TEXT>
