<HEADLINE> Chechen Committee Condemns Ferry Hijacking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Ankara-based Caucasian,
Chechen Solidarity Committee today Called for a peaceful solution
to the Trabzon ferry hijacking by pro-chechen militants.
</P>
<P>
Dursun Bolat, humanitarian aid representative of the committee,
said in Istanbul that his organization disapproves of the
hijacking and the using of passengers as hostages, which he fears
may cause friction between Turkey and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Bolat said he hopes for an immediate bloodless end to the
crisis, saying "if they reach Istanbul, being a Chechen I may go
to meet them."
</P>
<P>
In a separate statement, the Caucasian, Chechen Solidarity
Committee said that the Trabzon hijacking was "a response to the
genocide being perpetrated on the Chechen people by Russia."
</P>
<P>
It said that this act of protest was similar to the one by
Chechens in Kizlyar.
</P>
<P>
The statement said, "We know that those who carried out this
action do not intend to shed blood.
</P>
<P>
"We want our state to refrain from the tough action against
them and to end this action in a bloodless manner."
</P>
<P>
It added that the organization is ready to contribute to
bringing about a peaceful settlement of the hijacking, claiming it
did not wish to see any of the Russian hostages harmed.
</P>
<P>
A group of pro-Chechen rebels hijacked the "Avrasya" passenger
ship in Turkey's Black Sea port city of Trabzon Tuesday night and
the ship was heading westward for another Turkish Black Sea port
city of Samsun this morning.
</P>
<P>
The ship was to sail from Trabzon to Russia's Sochi harbor,
some 200 people on board, most of them Russians, are held as
hostages.
</P>
<P>
Muhammed Tokcan, head of the pro-Chechen rebels, has reportedly
said that they would free the ship if Russian troops stopped
fighting against the Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
He called for the release of their friends at their Chechen
villages besieged by Russian troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
