<HEADLINE> Unita Resumes Sending Guerrillas to Assembly Point </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The opposition National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (Unita) today resumed
sending its guerrillas to an assembly point at Vila Nova in the
central Huambo Province, a UN official said tonight.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Paulo Rodrigues Do Nascimento, spokesman
of the UN probe team, to reporters here.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that 116 Unita fighters are quartering at Vila
Nova town today while the government's rapid intervention police
force too started massing in Uige city in northern Angola today.
</P>
<P>
The quartering of soldiers began on November 20, 1955, one
year after the two sides reached agreements on peace in the
country.
</P>
<P>
But Unita stopped the process on December 4, complaining that
its troops were attacked the previous day by government soldiers
near Soyo, an oil producing town in northern Angola.
</P>
<P>
Nascimento, however, accused Unita of failing to quarter
its soldiers at three other assembly points at Huambo, Uige and
Bengo provinces as scheduled. 
</P>
