<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-17 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-Chechen Militants Still Hijack Ferryboat in Black Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Pro-Chechen militants who
hijacked a Black Sea ferry to oppose the Russian attack on Chechen
rebels today appeared ready to release some of the 200 hostages on
board, showing signs that the hostage crisis could be brought to
an end without bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
The hijackers claimed their struggle was for the freedom of
their homeland, but it became increasingly apparent that they
would be content with the publicity they created.
</P>
<P>
The militants seized the 3,383-ton Panama-registered ferryboat
Avrasya at the Turkish Black Sea port of Trabzon Tuesday night,
taking the 144 passengers, most of them are Russians, and 55 crew
members as hostages.
</P>
<P>
A local police official was reportedly injured in a skirmish
with the masked militants. They later forced the ship, operating
between the Crimean port of Sochi and the Turkish port, to head
for Istanbul, 1,200 kilometers west.
</P>
<P>
Muhammed Tokcan, leader of the hijackers, denied the reports
that they had used violence on the passengers and there were
scores of wounded.
</P>
<P>
"The reason why we have commandeered this ship is very
simple: I do not know what the world is thinking, but what we are
after is saving our homeland, living with our own culture ... and
we do not think there is a force which can prevent that, because,
our only choice is between freedom and death. This struggle will
go on until the Russians withdraw and a confederation of Caucasus
peoples is established," Tokcan told the Anatolia news agency in a
radio interview.
</P>
<P>
He said they would take the ship to Istanbul, and decide the
next step there.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Tokcan told a television that they would act "in
accord with people's wishes" in Istanbul, thus hinting a peaceful
end to the episode.
</P>
<P>
Turkish officials reportedly said some of the passengers would
be freed in the port of Sinop, about 600 kilometers further west.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Deniz Baykal said although preparations could
have been made for all contingencies, "the important thing is to
bring the incident to a conclusion without leading to a clash or
bloodshed."
</P>
<P>
Baykal confirmed that Moscow had handed a note to the Turkish
Embassy in Moscow, "containing a justified call for measures to
ensure the safety of the Russian hostages."
</P>
<P>
But, Foreign Ministry spokesman Nurettin Nurkan dismissed
Moscow's allegations that Turkey was training Chechen fighters on
its territory and providing medical treatment to the wounded
rebels.
</P>
<P>
Nurkan said the hijackers will be tried in Turkey, adding that
it was unknown yet whether the ferryboat will be allowed into the
Bosphorus, one of the world's busiest waterways.
</P>
<P>
The recent crisis with the Chechens in Russia began on January
9, when rebels slipped past border guards and seized hostages in
Dagestan to dramatize their demand for a Russian troop withdrawal
from Chechnya. Russian troops blocked the Chechens from returning
to Chechnya with their hostages.
</P>
<P>
Russian troops entered into Chechnya, a largely Moslem republic
in Caucasus Mountains seeking to breakaway from Russia, in
December 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960118.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-17 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
