<HEADLINE> New Duma Speaker Pledges Impartiality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The newly-elected Chairman of
the State Duma (the lower House of the Russian Parliament),
Gennady Seleznyov, told reporters today that he would "stand above
party interests and will not lobby the interests of one faction in
prejudice to other factions".
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov, 48, nominated by the Communist Party, was elected
Duma speaker by 231 votes this afternoon in the third round of the
secret ballot thus surpassing the required number of 226 votes
necessary for the election.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with reporters here soon after the voting,
Seleznyov denied assumptions made by some politicians, in
particular members of the Liberal Democratic Party of Vladimir
Zhirinovsky and the pro-government "Our Home Is Russia" bloc, that
the Communist Party faction, which has the majority in the lower
House, would talk to other factions "from a position of strength".
</P>
<P>
"That's totally untrue," he pointed out. "On the contrary,
Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov has from the very
beginning proposed that everyone work constructively." "There is
no position of strength in the faction's conduct and any
corresponding reprimands are groundless," he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the issue of no-confidence in the government,
Seleznyov, former editor of the Communist Party daily Pravda and
deputy speaker of the previous Duma, said that his party does not
intend to raise the issue, stressing, "At least not tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
"We will see which proposals the government headed by (Viktor)
Chernomyrdin will introduce after the shifts which have taken
place within it" recently, the new Duma speaker said.
</P>
<P>
The new Duma was elected on December 17, 1995, with the
Communist Party winning over one third of its total 450 seats --
157. 
</P>
</TEXT>
