<HEADLINE> More Senior Officials Run for Greek Premiership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Athens, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Two top officials of the ruling
panhellnic socialist movement (PASOK) of Greece declared their
decision to run for the premiership today.
</P>
<P>
This happened less than one day away from a parliamentary group
meeting at which a new greek prime minister will be elected to
replace Andreas Papandreou, who resigned monday for health reason.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos, who has been deputizing
bed-ridden Papandreou for nearly two months until Papandreou's
resignation, announced his candidature at today's PASOK central
committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
Announcing his decision, Tsohatzopoulos provided assurances
that if elected, current economic policy will be continued.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that greece can respond to the
challenge of european economic and monetary union and participate
in the third phase of european unification.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, former Deputy Prime Minister Yiannis Haralambopoulos
also stated he would be a candidate for the premiership.
</P>
<P>
All together there are four senior PASOK officials who have
decided to take part in the race. Defence Minister Gerasimos
Arsenis and former Inudstry Minister Costas Simitis announced
their decision tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the constitution, a new premier must be elected by
the ruling party's parliamentary group within a three-day period
following the promulgation of the presidential decree on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
The presidential decree on the election of a new prime
minister, as requested by the constitution, was signed by
Papandreou last night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
