<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-17 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Head Activates "Poverty Clock" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- James Gustave Speth,
the Administrator of the the United Nations Development Programme
(UNDP), started a "poverty clock" in the northern lobby of the
U.N. building today.
</P>
<P>
The clock ticks every time another person joins the ranks of
the poor, some 47 a minute or more than 67,000 every day. It was
set up in the U.N. lobby to recognize 1996 as the International
Year for the Eradication of Poverty.
</P>
<P>
"We must never forget that behind every tick of the clock
there is a face, a person, a life," said Speth.
</P>
<P>
Three of the people whose lives have been touched by poverty
but who are working their way out of poverty traveled to the U.N.
from Zimbabwe, Bolivia and Harlem of New York and told their tales
of fighting against poverty in their communities:
</P>
<P>
-- Betty Bangira, a Zimbabwean mother of four, found her life
changed when her community joined with five others to create an
irrigation project in one of the country's desertified provinces:
</P>
<P>
-- Luis Ticona Mamani, an indigenous Aymara of the Bolivian
highlands, is now the director of an association of alpaca
herdsmen which has tripled incomes of families in the region.
</P>
<P>
-- Lenore Cola, a mother of three and a Harlem resident whose
family was homeless for four years, became involved in 1989 in a
street library program for children and their parents.
</P>
<P>
"This event is a cause for both alarm and optimism," said UNDP
Administrator Speth.
</P>
<P>
"Alarm because we are turning on a poverty clock which will
remind us that each day another 67,000 people join the ranks of
the poor. That's about 25 million people a year, most of whom will
be in the developing world, and 70 per cent of whom will be
female.
</P>
<P>
"Optimism because the international community now recognizes
the urgency of this problem, realizes what must be done and is
taking steps to halt, indeed reverse, this grim trend."
</P>
<P>
He said that UNDP has made poverty eradication the overarching
goal of its programs, working through 135 offices in developing
countries, and building its expertise in the area.
</P>
<P>
The agency is supporting developing countries as they build or
strengthen national poverty eradication strategies, setting timed
targets for progress, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
