<HEADLINE> US Fed Reports Economy Growing Modestly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve
(Fed) said today that the U.S. economy was "growing at a generally
modest pace" at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Fed's report, known as the "Beige Book" report from the
color of its cover, tracks economic activity in the 12 Federal
Reserve districts.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that the economic slowdown is widespread,
both geographically and across sectors.
</P>
<P>
The report said retail sales were below expectations, with
heavy discounting. Retailers in some regions in the South and
Midwest reported moderate growth, while reports from either coast
indicated mixed results.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing activity was also mixed, the report said. Output
has slowed in the Atlanta, New York, Philadelphia and Richmond
regions. Manufacturers in the Boston, Chicago, Cleveland and
Kansas City regions continued to operate at high levels.
</P>
<P>
Most regions reported a seasonal slowdown in single-family home
sales. Commercial real estate was improving in most districts.
</P>
<P>
Most manufacturers reported modest wage and salary increases.
"Prices remain generally stable," according to most accounts.
</P>
<P>
The "Beige Book" is released about every seven weeks. The
latest report was prepared by the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta
based on information collected before January 8.
</P>
<P>
Today's report came two weeks before the Fed's Open Market
Committee meets to consider possible changes in monetary policy.
Many analysts expect the Fed to lower interest rates again in the
first half of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
