<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Urges Full Compliance of Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, January 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke
reilerated here today there is no change in Dayton agreement and
called on the warring parties to fully comply with the peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
"We are insisting on the full compliance with the Dayton accord
that was signed in Paris at all times," said Holbrooke, who flew
in to Sarajevo earlier today to see whether the local parties were
sticking to the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, there are two problems facing the hard-brokered
peace deal: Bosnian Serbs' struggle to delay the handover of five
Sarajevo suburbs to government control, and the government's
refusal to free Serb prisoners of war (POW). Both acts are seen as
breach of the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy, the chief architect of the Dayton agreement,
said he was in Sarajevo just to see the ongoing peace process at a
crutial moment.
</P>
<P>
"On the eve of the first significant deadline, we try to assess
where we are," he said.
</P>
<P>
Midnight on Friday (23:00 GMT) is the first real test to the
implementation of the peace accord, by that time all the warring
armies are supposed to withdraw two kilometers each from the
frontline to carve out a zone of separation (ZOS). IFOR ground
troop commander Michael Walker said today at a press conference
that the parties have been cooperative so far in that aspect.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke also said the Muslim-led government should release
the Serb POWs by the deadline which also falls on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The prisoners exchange issue and the full account for missing
people are not linked issues," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The government suspended a mass exchange of POWs early this
week by demanding information and release of about 4,000 Muslims
instead of only 200 listed by the Serb side, thus posing a threat
to the full compliance of the peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke held talks with IFOR commander Admiral Leighton
Smith, High Representative Carl Bildt, representatives of the
five-nation Contact Group as well as Bosnian Muslim leaders Alija
Izetbegovic and Haris Silajdzic. He is scheduled to fly to
Belgrade tonight to meet with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic
on the issue of Serb Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, thousands of Serbs have fled their homes in
Sarajevo Serb districts which will be reverted to the rule of
Muslim-led government. A mass exodus is possible if a solution on
that issue is not found. 
</P>
</TEXT>
