<HEADLINE> Angola Warned to Keep Peace Moving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- US Ambassador to the UN
Madeleine Albright, after her arrival here today, warned Angolan
leaders the international community would withdraw support unless
they keep Angola's peace process moving.
</P>
<P>
The UN Security Council is running out of patience over
Angola's rocky progress toward ending its two decade-long civil
war, she warned.
</P>
<P>
"I bring from the President of the Security Council a warning
that the process has to keep moving or the international
community will simply say 'enough,'" Albright said.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who becomes President of the Security Council next
month, urged Angolan President Jose Eduardo Dos Santos and Unita
leader Jonas Savimbi to take chances in bringing last peace in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Dos Santos and Savimbi will meet in Gabon on Saturday, but
people consider that the talks are in jeopardy because of the
slow pace of demobilizing the rival armies.
</P>
<P>
Albright said she is looking forward to meeting Savimbi and
Dos Santos to deliver letters from the security council and US
president Bill Clinton and to discuss practical aspects of
national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(Unita) and Luanda reached peace agreements in Lusaka, Zambia in
November 1994, but the pacts are months behind schedule with each
accusing the other of frequently violating the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of people have been killed and millions
displaced in Angola's civil war which started on independence
from Portugal in 1975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
