<HEADLINE> IGADD Sub-Region Has Another Year Of Good Cereal Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The food aid needs in the
Inter-Governmental Authority on Drought and Development (IGADD)
region has droped 50 percent to 0.6 million metric tons thanks to
another year of good harvest.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by a food situation report distributed
today here by IGADD Early Warning and Food Information System.
</P>
<P>
The report said, cereals production in the IGADD sub-region in
1995 is estimated at 18.2 million tons, slightly lower than the
bumper harvest of 1994/95.
</P>
<P>
The report contributed the good harvest to favourable rainfall
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The report also attributed the high food production in 1995 to
increased input supply, particularly in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, cereal production is 13-30 percent
above average in Kenya and Ethiopia, two-four percent above
average in Sudan and Uganda, and below average by as much as 50
percent in Eritrea and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that "the good harvests of the past two
successive years will contribute significantly to the
sub-region's recovery from acute food shortages caused by the
1993 drought, when cereal production fell to 14.6 million metric
tons, 11 percent below normal".
</P>
<P>
It said, "the sub-region's net food deficit is expected to
drop by 16 percent from last year's level to 1.6 million mt".
</P>
<P>
The IGADD includes Djibouti, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Kenya,
Somalia, Sudan and Uganda. enditem

=01182021

=01182015

18/01/96 20:22 GMT
nnnn
