<HEADLINE> Syrian Foreign Minister on Next Round of Talks with Israel in Maryland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Shara disclosed here today that Syria is attaching great
importance to the coming round of talks between Syria and Israel,
due to be held on January 24 in the U.S. State of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with his French
counterpart Herve de Charette this evening, following a meeting
between Syrian President Hafez al-Assad and the visiting French
foreign minister, al-Shara said that Syria is serious about
achieving a just and comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that peace must be in line with international
resolutions, and must lead to an end of Israeli occupation and
withdrawal to the June 4, 1967 borders, adding that peace ought
not be at the expense of Syria.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shara further stated that the coming round of negotiations
will focus on the issue of security arrangements, indicating that
the coming months will witness tangible progress along the road to
peace.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured Syria's Golan Heights in the 1967 Middle East
war. Security arrangements after proposed Israeli withdrawal from
the Golan constitute the key issue in the peace talks between the
two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
